<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Parliament Adopts Resolution on Domestic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The lower house of India's
parliament (Lok Sabha) today unanimously adopted a resolution
calling for probity and accountability in public life and a
vigorous national campaign to check population growth, the Press
Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, moved by Speaker P.A. Sangma at the end of a
six-day special session to commemorate the Golden Jubilee of
India's independence, was passed by thumping of desks by members.
</P>
<P>
During the past six days, debates had focused on the burning
problems facing the country such as corruption, poverty and
population growth.
</P>
<P>
The Lok Sabha, through the resolution, also committed itself to
ridding the polity of criminalization, enforcing radical electoral
reforms and achieving universal primary education by the year
2005.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, the House called for efficient use of
resources, avoidance of wastes and priority to infrastructure
development.
</P>
<P>
It committed itself to elimination of poverty, securing social
justice and balanced regional development.
</P>
<P>
The House was adjourned sine die after adopting the resolution.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
