<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Bans Activities of Islamic Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Algeria has decided to impose
a ban on the activities of Abbas Madani, leader of the Islamic
Salvation Front (ISF), Radio Algiers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Madani will be confined to the house where he currently lives
and his guests will be limited to his family members, Algerian
Interior Ministry announced the decision through the Radio.
</P>
<P>
Madani has been informed that any new violation of the
conditions upon which he was released will send him back to prison.
</P>
<P>
The ISF leader was sentenced to 12 years in prison in 1992 in a
military-backed government crackdown on Islamic fundamentalism. He
was set free on July 15 this year under conditional release
measures which were intended by the Algerian authorities to ease
the tension caused by escalating violence.
</P>
<P>
Following a horrifying massacre in Sidi Moussa in which more
than 300 villagers were killed by Islamic militants, Madani
addressed an open message to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan on
August 30 expressing "his readiness to make an appeal to stop
bloodshed immediately, preparatory to embarking on a dialogue that
may lead Algeria to the realm of security." 
</P>
</TEXT>
