<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Carrier Launches Two US Simulation Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Long-March rocket
carrier, containing two simulation iridium satellites owned by the
American electronic giant Motorola, was successfully launched in
Taiyuan, capital of north China's Shanxi Province, at 10:00 this
evening.
</P>
<P>
The carrier, which was based on the Long-March-2-III and was
the first of its type launched, sent the two satellites into the
preset orbit from the Taiyuan Satellite Launching Center.
</P>
<P>
It is the 47th flight of the Long-March carrier family.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the Xi'an Satellite Sensing and Control
Center in Xi'an, capital city of northwestern Shaanxi Province,
the second section of the rocket separated from the distributor
after 11 minutes of flight.
</P>
<P>
The distributor brought the two simulation satellites into a
holding pattern at a perigee of 181.8 km and apogee of 674.7 km,
slid for over 40 minutes, and finally changed track to discharge
the two satellites at the preset orbit.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the launch is to check the performance and
quality of the Long-March-2-III carrier and the Taiyuan Launching
Center, a preparatory step before the future official launch of
two Motorola iridium satellites.
</P>
<P>
Iridium satellites are a new type of personal
telecommunications system developed by Motorola. A total of 66
iridium satellites will be sent into the orbit at six levels.
</P>
<P>
The 66 iridium satellites will be sent spaceward by rocket
carriers manufactured in the United States, Russia and China, at
22 per country.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the United States and Russia are carrying out
launches of the iridium satellites with US-made Delta rocket
carriers and Russian-made proton carriers.
</P>
<P>
The China Rocket Carrier Technology Research Institute
developed the upgraded model of the Long-March-2-III especially
for launching iridium satellites.
</P>
<P>
The three-stage rocket carrier is 40 m in length, 3.35 m in
diameter and weighs 213 tons when launched, and has an additional
distributor to send satellites from the initial holding pattern to
the final, elliptic orbit, discharging them in succession,
according to Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract signed with Motorala, the Taiyuan center is
scheduled to begin official launch of the iridium satellites later
this year and the 22 satellites will be sent into the orbit in the
coming few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
