<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on African Environment Starts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A three-day workshop to build
institutional and technical capacity for preparing State of the
Environment (SOE) reports opened in Harare today.
</P>
<P>
The workshop will provide a forum for participants to learn about
the different technical aspects of environmental reports, exchange
information on the development, approaches, uses and constraints to
SOE reporting.
</P>
<P>
It also aims at developing a multi-disciplinary regional network
of SOE practitioners.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 senior government and non-governmental organizations
managers from Kenya, Uganda and Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries are attending the workshop.
</P>
<P>
Director of the World Conservation Union regional office for SADC
Yemi Katerere said, "SOE reports are critical to decision making but
because every member of society has a custodial obligation to the
environment, SOE practitioners must ensure a broad ownership at all
stages of the environmental reporting process."
</P>
<P>
Katerere, who also is one of the workshop's organizers, said,
"An integrated and participatory approach is vital to ensure that
all needs and concerns are accounted for so that the ultimate product
is useful and relevant to audiences ranging from governments to
grass-roots communities."
</P>
<P>
All SADC countries have prepared at least one report on their
environment over the past fiver years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
