<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Rejects Lawsuit Against Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A Cairo court today threw out a
lawsuit filed by an Egyptian lawyer against Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu for his alleged part in the desecration of
Islamic and Christian symbols by Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo district court dismissed the case citing lack of
direct personal interest, and ordered the lawyer to pay litigation
expenses, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer, Mustafa Ashoub, sued Netanyahu in July, holding him
responsible for drawings that insulted the Prophet Mohammed and
the Virgin Mary, and maintaining that the posters have deeply hurt
religious feelings of Muslims all over the world.
</P>
<P>
He demanded 10 billion U.S. dollars in compensation which he
said would be spent to build mosques and churches and help the
families of Palestinians died in the seven-year-old Intifada
(uprising).
</P>
<P>
He was well aware that even if he wins, there would be no way
for the Egyptian court decision to be enforced in Israel, not to
mention that the case is of only moral value.
</P>
<P>
However, it is a legal and peaceful way to express his hurt
feelings, according to the plaintiff, who said the case was based
on Article 163 of the Civil Code, which stipulates that anyone who
causes harm to any other must pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
Violence raged across the West Bank in June after an Israeli
woman put up in Hebron offensive posters depicting Mohammed as a
pig stomping on the Koran, the Islamic Holy Book. Several days
later, a picture with Virgin Mary painted with the head of a cow
appeared in an Israeli magazine.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli woman who drew the insulting leaflet is now facing
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
