<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's AIDS Fighting Urged to Go With Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Anti-AIDS fighting should be
intergrated into family planning efforts in Africa where
heterosexual contacts are the primary reason behind HIV
infection, worldwide aid organizatin, the Pathfinder
International urged today.
</P>
<P>
The second-placed mode of HIV infection in Africa is through
the mother to the new-born, said Daniel Pellegrom, the President
of the Boston-based worldwide aid organization.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Pellegrom said, integration of the prevention of
sexual transmitted diseases (STDs) and family planning services
will be a key factor in improving reproductive health and
reducing HIV transmission in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Pellegrom made the remarks when launching a book on the topic
published by the Pathfinder.
</P>
<P>
The rapid spread of HIV-AIDS and continued high population
growth are inter-related problems posing serious challenges to
Africa, which hosts at least 60 percent of HIV carriers in the
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ideally, such integration should take place in an environment
where, depending on clients' needs, a comprehensive selection of
STD/HIV-AIDS/family planning services is provided to clients by
one service provider during the same visit, the book explained.
</P>
<P>
Thus can minimize missed opportunities for screening for and
treating STDs, avoid wasting resources, and become more cost
effective and more convenient for clients, said the book.
</P>
<P>
The book is titled as "An African Response to the Challenge of
Integrating STD/HIV-AIDS Services into Family Planning Programs."
</P>
<P>
An estimated 27.9 million people worldwide had been infected
with HIV by mid-1996, of which 19 million people from sub-Saharan
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
