<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Maps out Reproductive Health Strategy for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has introduced a 10-year reproductive health strategy for its
African member states.
</P>
<P>
The plan, drawn up by experts working under the WHO's regional
office for Africa, is called Reproductive Health Strategy, to be
implemented from next year to 2007.
</P>
<P>
The document will be submitted to a five-day meeting of African
health ministers beginning today in Sun City, South Africa,local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO's officials, reproductive health is the state of
complete mental, physical and social well-being in all matters related
to the reproductive system and its functions and processes.
</P>
<P>
African countries agreed to implement, for the next 20 years,the
concept adopted by the international conference on population and
development held three years ago in Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
WHO experts said major reproductive health problems in Africa are
related to issues as maternal mortality rate, at about 700 per 1000
live birth, considered the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The WHO study says if the plan is properly implemented, the ratio
of mothers dying at birth in Africa will be reduced by at least 20
percent over the next 10 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Advocates Arab Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Egyptian official
said today Egypt is seeking the establishment of a free trade zone
within the Arab world, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An Arab free trade zone helps "to increase the trade volume and
to remove obstacles to the movement of goods and capital between
them, and finally lead to the creation of an Arab Common Market."
said Ahmed Gowaili, minister of trade and supply.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has so far signed a free trade agreement with Jordan and
is in the final stages of concluding similar pacts with Tunisia,
Morocco, Lebanon, Kuwait, Syria and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that the scope of current inter-Arab
trade does not exceed 8 percent of the total amount of their
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
And there exists a huge trade deficit in the Arab countries'
dealings with the rest of the world - their imports amount to 150
billion U.S. dollars but non-oil exports stay at 2 billion dollars
per year, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a committee supervising the implementation of Great
Arab Free Trade Zone (GAFTZ) held its premier meeting here today
which was attended by chief delegates of member states of the Arab
League (AL).
</P>
<P>
The GAFTZ committee is entrusted to map out annual customs and
taxes reduction programs and settle commercial disputes among
member states. It is required to submit its report to the AL
Economic and Social Council in November.
</P>
<P>
As a prelude to the common market, the AL Ministerial Council
adopted a resolution in 1996 calling for the GAFTZ to be
established by 1998.
</P>
<P>
The resolution stated that non-tariff barriers should be
eliminated and tariffs gradually reduced until complete
liberalization was reached by the end of the year 2007. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
