<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Appeals for Political Solution in Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- France today again appealed to
the warring sides of the Congo Republic to "renounce military
option" and continued to recognize Pascal Lissouba, whose
presidential term expired mid-night Sunday, as the country's
president.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the parties to renounce military option and call for
a return to cease-fire, badly needed for creating the conditions
of a lasting solution," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Jacques Rummelhardt, who called Lissouba "president".
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court of Congo has decided to prolong the
mandate of Lissouba, because the fighting between government
forces and militia-men of former president, General Denis Sassou
Nguesso, had blocked the holding of presidential election
originally scheduled for July 27.
</P>
<P>
The verdict was rejected by Sassou Nguesso, who now considers
the power in the country as "vacant".
</P>
<P>
"The persistent shooting of heavy weapons in Brazzaville
remains very worrying," said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman welcomed the summit held last Saturday in
Gabonese capital Libreville by Lissouba and Gabonese President
Omar Bongo, who has been mediating the conflict in Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sahnoun, the envoy of the United Nations and
Organization of African Unity, issued the communique after the
summit, which said that Lissouba and Bongo had agreed upon some
new proposals aimed at "establishing a climate of confidence and
reconciliation by gathering the political forces of the country
to the administration of the transitional period." 
</P>
</TEXT>
