<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Experiences Hottest August in Recorded History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Belgium has just experienced
its hottest Summer in recorded history as the month of August came
to an end to the joy of otherwise sun-chasing populace here.
</P>
<P>
The average mean temperature in the past August was 21.2
degrees Celsius, the highest since record-keeping started in 1833,
according to the Belgian Royal Institute of Meteorology.
</P>
<P>
The previous record for hottest August was posted in 1911 when
the average mean temperature soared to 20.9 degrees. The average
temperature for August is 16.8 degrees in this country.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday before rain storms set in as the prelude of autumn,
the temperature shot up to 31.9 degrees for a hottest single day
in the month.
</P>
<P>
Yet the hottest single day registered a thermometer reading of
37.4 degrees Celsius on July 27, 1947.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologist De Bondridder at the institute explained that
Belgium was in the past month under an unsubdued influence of two
high-pressure masses, one coming from the African coast while the
other from the Baltic Sea.
</P>
<P>
Sandwiched in between, Belgium had a rather hot summer caused
by a subtropical air which scared tourists away to seaside resorts
instead.
</P>
<P>
Though neighboring France has been blaming the depletion of
ozone caused mainly by the exhausts from motor vehicles for its
unusually hot summer, Belgian meteorologists held the two
high-pressure masses responsible to their hottest August in
history.
</P>
<P>
Ozone is believed to serve as a protective layer in the
atmosphere by absorbing solar ultraviolet radiation. It not only
helps produce a maximum temperature but also effectively blocks
all solar radiation of wavelengths less than 290 nanometers from
reaching the Earth's surface, where it would injure or kill most
living things. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
