<HEADLINE> Kromah Denied Involvement in S. Leona Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's former warlord Alhaji
Kromah today denied accusations that fighters of his defunct
faction were involved in the current civil war in the neighboring
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The new President of Liberia Charles Taylor allegedly accused
of late that some ex-fighters of Liberia's United Liberation
Movement (ULIMO) were fighting along with Sierra Leone's
traditional hunters known as Kamajors against soldiers of the
military government.
</P>
<P>
The move would lead to destabilization in Liberia where peace
has just emerged at the end of a seven-year civil war, Taylor
warned, according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
However, Kromah, a major rival of Taylor, denied the
allegation, saying that it was too early to be making this kind
of accusations.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know from where he (Taylor) is speaking, but to the
best of my knowledge I'm not aware of any ULIMO personnel
involved in any kind of war anywhere," Kromah said, quoted by the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The former key warlord said he had no intention to bring
destabilization into the country, which has been ravaged in the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
"We have repeatedly declared our commitment to the fact that we
will not allow anybody to bring war into this country or to bring
any fighting into this country any more," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is our solemn commitment," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Kromah was not sure whether some of the former ULIMO men
were fighting in Sierra Leone beyond his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
During the Liberian civil war, there were some ULIMO
militiamen fighting in Sierra Leone in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
"All what you think of could be possible. But at this moment,
all we know is there are fightings between the Kamajors and the
government forces" in that country, Kromah said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kromah, he now has good relations with Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Only three or four days ago, " He (Taylor) talked to me on the
telephone line from Abuja and we had a very good conversation,"
Kromah said, adding that nothing of ULIMO was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
To maintain peace in Liberia is now one of the major tasks for
leaders in west Africa, who put special emphasis on the issue in
the just-concluded sub-regional summit two days ago.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in Sierra Leone, a result of the May 25 coup which
overthrew the legitimate government of that country and has posed
threat to the peace and security of the sub-region, is also high
on the summit agenda.
</P>
<P>
The leaders have decided to impose comprehensive sanctions and
embargo on Sierra Leone to force the military junta to step down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
