<HEADLINE> $26 Million Marijuana Seized in Idaho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. law enforcement
officers seized marijuana worth 26 million U.S. dollars in the
mountainous area of Idaho in August in a series of raids, the New
York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The raids was made by a joint force of Federal, state and local
law enforcement officers at a time of fall marijuana harvest in
the area. Some of the plots were four years old.
</P>
<P>
"I could't believe how they'd done it for so long right under
our noses," said Sheriff Jim Nelson of Washington County, were
most of the plots were situated.
</P>
<P>
The authorities arrested in four raids 10 people on two felony
counts each of conspiracy to manufacture marijuana and conspiracy
to distribute marijuana.
</P>
<P>
Law-enforcement experts said that the discovery of outdoor
marijuana farms in Idaho underscores a national trend in which
growers are setting up increasingly sophisticated outdoor and
indoor growing operations to supply millions of pounds of marijuana
for American consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
