<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriot Trade Unions Call for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Greek and Turkish Cypriot
trade unions today reaffirmed their adherence to the principles
of peace and their determination to work for consolidating peace
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In a joint declaration issued today, 15 Greek and Turkish
Cypriot trade unions expressed disappointment at the failure of
the initiatives undertaken by the U.N. in the search for a lasting
solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was issued after a peace rally at the Ledra
Palace Hotel in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia,
marking the International Day of Peace.
</P>
<P>
The trade unions called on all the parties involved, the U.N.,
and other organizations and countries to expedite their efforts to
ensure that the course of peace is safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
The trade unions reiterated their firm belief that a just
and viable solution to the Cyprus problem will serve the cause
of peace in Cyprus and the region.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the solution should be based on
U.N. resolutions and with "full guarantee on the human and trade
union rights and a unitary economy, without any form of
discrimination."
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration was handed over to Peter Schmitz,
U.N. peace-keeping force senior political advisor, who
represented U.N. at the peace rally.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the declaration, Schmitz called it a very encouraging
sign for the future, which makes the U.N. feel very much heartened
to continue with its work to bring about a peaceful settlement to
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said he will convey the declaration to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in New York.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Trade Union Coordinating Committee,
General Secretary of the Cyprus Workers' Confederation
Michalakis Ioannou stressed that on the occasion of today's
International Day of Peace, Greek and Turkish Cypriot trade
unions join force in demanding from the U.N., the international
community and the island's leadership to "hear the voice of the
majority of the people and work toward a fair solution which
will bring peace to the island."
</P>
<P>
Ioannou stated that only if peace is achieved can the trade
unions work constructively and effectively to improve people's
living standards on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot South and Turkish
Cypriot North since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and took
over the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed
coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
