<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Calls for New Strategy for South-South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Group-77 Chambers of Commerces
and Industry (CCI) Chairman Tariq Sayeed today called on G-77
states to adopt a new strategy to boost South-South cooperation and
evolve a balanced, just and equitable global economic order.
</P>
<P>
"The current global behaviors indeed calls for evolving a new
strategy," Tariq Sayeed told a CCI trade meeting opening here
today, citing a 2,100-billion-U.S.-Dollar foreign debt of the
third world in 1996 and trade barriers by developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Facing the situation, the developing countries first "should
unite ourselves and forge cooperation to address the crucial
issues emanating from trade barriers, conditionalities of IMF,
prolems of trade deficit and mounting trade burden," he said.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 members should boost their contacts "in a big way
through various means" such as setting up a development bank, an
insurance company, an exhibition authority and an information
network, he said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the G-77 states "should try to improve our system by
adopting modern techniques both for production and investment" so
as to enter into negotiation with the North and "to evolve a
balanced, just and equitable economic order," Sayeed noted.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 should "make collective efforts" to remove invisible
trade barriers like anti-dumping, environment, child labor and
form groups of experts to help strengthen their quality control,
professional management and worldwide marketing, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
This is " a two-pronged strategy" the developing world has to
do, he said.
</P>
<P>
The development of the third world needs support from
developed nations and also in the larger interest of the latter,
Sayeed said, urging more frequent contacts and dialogues between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The developing countries now account for about 25 percent of
the world trade, compared with 20 percent a decade ago, according
to the date available at the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Karachi-headquartered G-77 group, comprising 132
developing countries from Asia, Africa, Latin America and the
Pacific and Carribean region, was founded at the first U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development meeting in Geneva in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The group set up CCI in 1986 in a bid to mobilize the
participation of their private sector for economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Set to Unify Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) is now facing the most important task of unifying
laws applicable to the Palestinian people, said a PLC leader today.
</P>
<P>
Rawhi Fatouh, secretary general and a member of the PLC, made
this remark during an open discussion with journalists held today
in Ramallah, West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said there are different laws in Palestine, with Jordanian
laws being applied in the West Bank and Egyptian laws, in the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
The PLC has submitted to the Cabinet 26 draft laws for
consideration, and the most important one is the "Basic Law" which
will be the temporary constitution during the interim period, he
said. Those draft laws will be discussed when the PLC opens its
session on September 15, he said.
</P>
<P>
As most parliaments of other countries have specific
committees, the PLC also has the Refugee Committee, the Jerusalem
Committee and the Land and Settlement Committee because of the
unique Palestinian situation, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt has agreed to send five experts to the PLC
to assist in the drafting of legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
