<HEADLINE> U.S. Considering Delegation to Diana's Funeral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The White House, State
Department and U.S. Embassy in London are considering who will
lead an official delegation to Saturday's funeral for Princess
Diana, who was killed in a car crash in Paris at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart, who is with a vacationing
President Bill Clinton on Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts, said
it is unlikely a delegation will be named before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
News reports quoted Lockhart as telling reporters, "When I
know, you will know."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lockhart released the text of cable Clinton sent to
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, restating his sympathy over the
death of the princess.
</P>
<P>
Clinton wrote, "Hillary and I were deeply shocked by the news
of Princess Diana's passing. Please accept our personal
condolences, as well as those of the American people."
</P>
<P>
Similar dispatches were sent to Queen Elizabeth II, Prince
Charles and Diana's brother, Charles Spencer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
