<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nile Water Not Polluted: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian official said today
that the Nile water is not polluted by phosphate carried by a
barge that sank into the river Sunday after a collision.
</P>
<P>
Analysis of water samples taken from the site where the barge
sank has shown that the water was not affected by the phosphate
and there will be no adverse effect on fish, plants or drinking
water, said an official at the Ministry of Public Works.
</P>
<P>
The barge ferrying 370 tonnes of phosphate sank into the Nile
Sunday after it collided with another barge in Beni Suef, some 90
kilometers south of the capital. All six crew on board were
rescued.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Ismail Sallam said his ministry has taken
all precautions to ensure that Nile water was not polluted.
</P>
<P>
According to Mohammed Raga'i Shatla, director of Prevention
Medicine Department in Beni Suef, citizens in the region had been
provided with temporary sources of water before it was proved that
there was no leakage of phosphates in the water.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces and frogmen lifted the barge out of the river
and the movement of river boats and ships is back to normal, said
an official from the Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
The phosphates were tightly packed in huge plastic bags
impermeable to water, according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian authorities closed several outlets on the lower
branches of the Nile to forestall any pollution immediately after
the accident.
</P>
<P>
The 6,700-kilometer Nile River is the longest in the
world. Running 1,530 kilometers inside Egypt, it is the lifeline
of Egyptians on whose banks and delta up to 95 percent of the
population are living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
