<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Refugees Protest UNRWA Budget Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian refugees in
Lebanon went on strike today in protest of a U.N. organ's decision
to cut 7 million U.S. dollars from its 1997 relief budget.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese official National News Agency said the protesters
burnt tires at the entrance of their camps, closed their shops and
staged a sit-in in front of the offices of U.N. Relief and Works
Agency (UNRWA), the International Red Cross Committee (IRCC) and
the UN Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL).
</P>
<P>
The refugees, coming from eight of the 10 camps in Lebanon,
stated in a memo presented to these organizations their
difficulties that the budget cut would bring about and called on
UNRWA to help them return to their homeland as stipulated by UN
General Assembly resolution 194.
</P>
<P>
This was the second strike of the Palestinian refugees since
UNRWA announced its reduction of this year's total budget of 54.7
million U.S. dollars on August 20 as a result of a 20 million
dollar deficit and lack of contributions from donor nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lebanese government criticized the UNRWA's
decision as an attempt to shift responsibilities to host
countries for solving social and economic problems of the
Palestinian refugees, who mainly live in Lebanon, Syria, Jordan
and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian refugees in Lebanon, classified as "temporary
residents", are kept away from the government services of Lebanon
and largely dependent on UNRWA for schooling, health care and camp
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
UNRWA, set up in 1950, is to care for the social welfare of the
3.3 million Palestinian refugees in the world, of whom 360,000 are
residing in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
