<HEADLINE> Angola Vows to Uproot Illiteracy by 2007 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 1, (Xinhua) -- Angola will begin to put into
force its anti-illiteracy plan in November in a bid to wipe out
illiteracy by 2007.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Domingos, Director of the Adult Education Department
in Angola's Ministry of Education made the pledge here today at
an occasion marking the international week for adult education
from September 1-8.
</P>
<P>
Domingos said that high illiteracy is posing as an obstacle to
economic development, and the fact has force the international
community into an effort to cut by half the Illiteracy worldwide
by the coming century.
</P>
<P>
Domingos said that some education centers will be established
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the illiterate people are women, mostly
living in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
In consideration of the specific condition in the country,
Domingos said, efforts will be made especially in the countryside
and, especially among women who have the least access to
education.  
</P>
