<HEADLINE> Iran Dismayed at Violence in Muslim World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian official today that
Iran is dismayed at the recent outbreak of violence in Algeria and
Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi condemned the
recent massacre of the civilians in Algeria and called on the
international community to deal with the "unprecedented crimes"
against innocent people in the north African country.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Algerian government to pave the way for
peaceful realization of the wishes of the Algerian nation.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified armed group perpetrated a horrible massacre
Thursday night in the town of Sidi Moussa, about 20 kilometers
south of the capital Algiers, killing more than 300 villagers.
</P>
<P>
The massacre was the gravest terrorist act witnessed by Algeria
since insurgency began five years ago when the military-backed
government canceled a parliament election in which the Islamic
Salvation Front appeared to win.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed concern over the recent carnage in
Tajikistan and denounced the recent "kidnaping" of the Mufti, the
top clergyman in the country who has the authority to interpret the
Muslim law.
</P>
<P>
"The Tajik nation has endured many hardships on the path to the
recent cessation of hostilities in the country," Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
It's incumbent upon all the national forces to respect the
recently concluded peace treaty and use everything at their
disposal to attain a comprehensive peace in their country, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
