<HEADLINE> 12 Arrested for Instigating Protest in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish police today
arrested 12 people in protest of the recently adopted eight-year
compulsory education law in Turkey's largest city of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
They have been accused of stirring up a group of 150 Islamists
to attack the ATV, a leading Turkish television station, on Sunday
night, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The protesters stormed into the downtown television studio,
disarming a guard, smashing windows and television equipment. They
fled before anti-terror police arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
Police said the protesters had shouted slogans against the new
eight-year compulsory education law, which was passed in the
Parliament last month.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Islamists have been greatly angered by the
new law, initiated by the government led by Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz to demand students finish eight years of compulsory
education before they are permitted to start religious study.
</P>
<P>
The law has actually forced the closure of a large number of
religious schools.
</P>
<P>
Since the Education Ministry worked out the reform bill, the
conservative Islamists have staged anti-government demonstrations
around the mosques in major cities, especially in Istanbul,
following their routine Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government, with the support of the military,
launched the education reform program aiming to curb the rapidly
growing fundamentalist force in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
