<HEADLINE> European Shares Up on Benign Economic Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all suspended last week's decline and recovered today, boosted by
a stronger dollar and faded worries on higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
On the London market, the FTSE 100 index ended more than 50
points ahead in quiet trading, with business subdued due to the
Labor Day holiday in the US.
</P>
<P>
Softer-than-expected consumer credit data today boosted the
market earlier by easing fears of an imminent interest rate hike.
The blue-chip index stood at 4,870.2, a gain of 52.7 points by the
close.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt rose on the back of a firmer dollar
and stronger futures and bond prices. The DAX-30 index closed with
a rise of 83.93 points at 3,989.96.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that volumes were thin due to a holiday in the US.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, stocks ended firmer, with takeover news in
the retail sector helping to give the market a boost. A stronger
dollar also provided support. The CAC-40 index finished 35.35
points up at 2,805.84.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that the current rising trend was
unlikely to last into Tuesday, with further falls in New York
likely and turbulence in Asia set to continue. 
</P>
