<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Asked to Meet EU Conditions for Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Poos, European Union
(EU) term president and foreign minister of Luxemburg, said here
today Turkey has to fulfill necessary conditions ahead of its EU
membership negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey should normalize its ties with Greece, change its
traditional policy towards Cyprus and improve its human rights
record," said Jacques Poos, who is on a one-day working visit to
Ankara, after a meeting with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot start to negotiate with Turkey for its bid for full
EU membership before these conditions are met," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he reaffirmed that Turkey is still a part of the EU
enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has earlier announced a report, known
as "Agenda 2000", excluding Turkey from the rank of prospective EU
membership candidates.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Cem, Poos had reportedly mentioned the
Kurdish problem, a highly sensitive issue to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He called for a political solution to the Kurdish issue,
adding that "the cultural autonomy of Kurds must be recognized."
</P>
<P>
In his part, Cem said that the Turkish government would make
efforts to overcome these difficulties in its full EU membership
drive, saying participation in the EU is part of Turkey's state
policy.
</P>
<P>
As for the humans rights issue, he said every country has its
own problems in this respect, and that Turkey would try to improve
its human rights record through practical means.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister, however, has repeatedly stated
that full EU membership is a target, not an obsession, for Turkey
and stressed that failure to become an EU member does not mean the
end of the world.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here pointed out that Turkey is not only annoyed at
not being considered by the EU, but also angered by the inclusion
of Cyprus in the EU enlargement talks to be held early next year.
</P>
<P>
Ankara said that the Cypriot government is not eligible to
enter the EU on behalf of the whole country composed of separated
Greek and Turkish communities.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into a Greek Cypriot south and Turkish
Cypriot north after Turkey landed troops on the east Mediterranean
island in 1974 following a pro-Athens coup. The Turkish Cypriots
have declared a breakaway republic recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been keen on becoming an EU member, but failed to
achieve the goal due to a number of controversial issues including
the Cyprus issue, a weak economy as well as its human rights
record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
