<HEADLINE> Britain's Sports Organs, Supermarkets to Mark Diana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's sporting
organizations and major supermarkets will mark the funeral of
Princess Diana by canceling scheduled events and close high
street stores.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, the England Football Association the
British government held emergency talks on re-scheduling matches
following the Buckingham Palace announcement that Diana's funeral
will be held Saturday morning at Westminster Abbey.
</P>
<P>
The Football League has postponed all division one, two and
three fixtures as a mark of respect for Princess Diana who died in
a tragic car crash in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Scottish Football Association (SFA) leaders are holding urgent
talks with the world football governing body FIFA and the British
government to decide whether the World Cup qualifying match
between Scotland and Belarus in Aberdeen should go ahead on the
day of the funeral.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the SFA said, "We will consult with the
international committee and take whatever further advice may be
necessary with Her Majesty's government, FIFA and our opponents
Belarus before any decision will be taken."
</P>
<P>
The rugby union program Saturday has also been called off and
officials confirmed there will be no competitive league fixtures.
</P>
<P>
The British Horseracing Board also announced that no race
meetings will take place on the day of the funeral. Chairman of
the Horseracing Board Lord Wakeham noted that the five meetings
that had been scheduled have all been canceled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain's high streets are likely to be deserted
Saturday morning as the country's major supermarket stores will
close to pay their respects to the dead princess.
</P>
<P>
The Tesco, Sainsbury and Cooperative supermarkets chains have
announced early today that their stores will stay shut until 2
pm.
</P>
<P>
The Harrods store, owned by Mohammed al Fayed whose son Dodi
Fayed was also killed in the car accident, is to close for the
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
