<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More AIDS Cases Detected in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The sudden death of
Britain's Princess Diana has thrown uncertainty onto a charity
gala for Action for AIDS scheduled to be held on September 23 in
Singapore, where more AIDS cases were detected in the first half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Local television reported today that organizers of the charity
gala had arranged for the princess to attend the gala dinner and
to visit AIDS patients here.
</P>
<P>
They had hoped to raise close to a million U.S. dollars to set
up a fund to subsidize medication for patients of HIV which causes
AIDS, the television report said.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, a total of 40 new cases of HIV infection were
reported between April and June this year, meaning a total of 73
Singaporeans have been infected during the first half of this
year. The figure is a little more than half of the new cases
detected for the whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
Of those infected with HIV this year, most were males, who
accounted for 92 percent of all cases. Almost half, or 47 percent,
of the infected were between 30 to 39 years and this formed the
largest affected age group.
</P>
<P>
Of the 73 new cases this year, 69 were infected through sexual
transmission. The rest were through intravenous drug use and from
mother to child.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Health Ministry said the number of new
cases of HIV infections reported each year has been increasing
since the first case was detected here in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Since then, 631 Singaporeans have been found to be infected
with HIV and 211 have died.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
