<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, September 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Export-Import Bank of Japan has signed an
agreement with the Bank of Thailand to offer 4 billion
U.S. dollars in loans to Thailand to help it prop up its foreign
reserves, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand Governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi said that the
funds from Japan will be used as standby credits to shore up
Thailand's official foreign reserves, which has dropped to 27.9
billion dollars as of August 14. (Thailand-Japan-Loan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Keizo Obuchi will be Japan's new foreign minister and
Hiroshi Mitsuzuka may be reappointed as the finance minister in
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's new cabinet, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kanezo Muraoka, who now serves as the chairman of the Liberal
Democratic Party's (LDP) Diet (parliament) Affairs Committee, will
likely become the chief cabinet secretary, Kyodo news service
quoted the party sources as saying. (Japan-Cabinet-Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Two Bosnian Croats were killed at their home in
Moslem-controlled Travnik in central Bosnia on weekend, causing
great panic among Croats in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said today that the two men, a
father and his son, were reportedly shot to death when they were
having dinner at home on Sunday evening. (Bosnia-Croatia-Killings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Floods triggered by heavy rains have hit six
counties in Romania, killing at least 20 people over the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
The State Agricultural Department said Tuesday the floods have
drowned 590,000 hectares of farmland so far this year and caused
damage equivalent to 108 million U.S. dollars. (Romania-Flooding)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
