<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Against British Official Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today lodged a protest
to the British government against an official document circulated
in the British Bases in this country that refers to the Turkish
Cypriot regime in the north as the "Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here, Cyprus government
spokesman Manolis Christofides described as "unacceptable" the
official document circulated Monday by the Commander of the
British Bases, Air Vice-Marshall Peter Millar.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cyprus government expects a "positive response"
from Britain to its representations and noted that Britain, as a
guarantor power of the Cyprus Republic and a U.N. Security Council
permanent member, should respect U.N. resolutions on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island in the wake of a failed coup of the Greek Cypriot
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared a breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus"(TRNC) in 1983, which was recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.N. resolutions have called upon "all states not to recognize
the purported state of the TRNC set up by secessionist acts and
not to facilitate or in any way assist the aforesaid secessionist
entity".
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Christofides said, the British acts were contrary to
the U.N. resolutions and for this reason a formal protest would be
lodged and relevant representations be made to the British
government through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the British Bases authorities in Cyprus
today issued a statement, apologizing for mistakenly referring to
the Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus as "the Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that it is the "clear policy of the
British government" that it does not recognize the Turkish
Cypriot regime led by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the former colonial power of Cyprus, retained two
Sovereign Base Areas (SBA) on the island, Dhekelia SBA on the
southeastern coast and Akrotiri SBA on the southwestern coast,
after Cyprus gained its independence in 1960.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
