<HEADLINE> Generator Contracts On China's Three Gorges Dam Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Contracts on 14
turbogenerators for the Three Gorges Dam project, the largest
hydro-electric project in the world, were signed here today.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng and Vice-premier Zou Jiahua attended the
signing ceremony in the Great Hall of the People where
representatives of China Three Gorges Corp. and Three Gorges
International Bid-Inviting Co. signed 740 million US dollars in
contracts with Alsthom of France, ABB of Switzerland, GE of
Canada, Siemens and a Norwegian company.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the State Development Bank signed loan
contracts with these companies' banks and loan-transfer contracts
with China Three Gorges Corp.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng congratulated the companies and expressed the hope that
they will strictly abide by the contracts, delivering equipment on
time, providing satisfactory after-sale service, and transferring
technology.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project is on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River and is a major part of China's effort to develop its
longest river. It will help prevent flooding along the river, and
have an annual generating capacity of 84.7 billion kw-hrs.
</P>
<P>
The project involves installing a total of 26 generating units.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the project started in December of 1994,
and a coffer dam is due to be built on the river in November at
the completion of the first phase of the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
