<HEADLINE> Thailand to Get World Bank Rescue Loans by December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of 350 million
U.S. dollar loans from the World Bank is expected to be
transferred to Thailand by December this year, the Government
House said today.
</P>
<P>
The fund is part of the 1.5 billion U.S. dollar loans that the
World Bank has promised to give Thailand in line with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) rescue package.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will approve the 1.5 billion U.S. dollar aid by
November as a result of its negotiations with the Bank of Thailand
last weekend, the Government House said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The release also said Thailand will seek additional 25 million
U.S. dollars in technical loan from the World Bank, 15 million of
which will be used to study ways to solve the problems concerning
58 suspended finance firms and public deposits.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said today the World Bank technical loan will
also be used to explore ways of overhauling the Thai central
bank's supervision over the country's financial institutions and
lay out an organizational framework for an IMF-initiated financial
restructuring agency.  
</P>
