<HEADLINE> Chinese Symposium On Women's Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A symposium organized by the
Chinese Ministry of Labor, the UN's International Labor
Organization, and the Shanghai Labor Bureau, on re-employment and
rights protection for women opened in Shanghai today.
</P>
<P>
The number of women working in China has increased remarkably
since 1978, accounting for 46.6 percent of the total number of
workers in 1996, according to an official of the Chinese Ministry
of Labor's Employment Department.
</P>
<P>
However, women employees, especially older ones with less
education and fewer skills, face great challenges during this
period of economic transition and structural adjustment, he said,
noting that 59.2 percent of the laid-off workers are women.
</P>
<P>
China has taken active steps to protect women's rights and to
work for women's employment, he said. In Shanghai, the country's
biggest commercial center, some 103,000 laid-off workers, 75
percent of whom are women, have found jobs.
</P>
<P>
The four-day symposium deals with the re-employment of laid-off
female workers, improving the professional skills of
under-employed women, and promoting equal employment of women in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
