<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Humanitarian Projects Completed in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Two humanitarian projects
were completed and inaugurated Monday in Jowhar town of Middle
Shabelle region, 90 km north of the Somali capital, Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The projects, a water supply system and a 5-km-long tarmac
road, were opened by Nur Mohamud Mohamed (Nur Shirbow), governor
of the region with the presence of Theo Kasber, acting chairman
of the European Union (EU) office in Somalia, and Vasilis
Petrsides, head of EU rehabilitation projects.
</P>
<P>
The two projects, funded by the EU's Somalia office, were
implemented by the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF0, and
an Italian aid agency CEFA.
</P>
<P>
The main project, the water supply system which took 14 months
to complete, will provide potable water to four quarters in
Jowhar town, while the tarmac road is already being used by the
traffic from Jowhar to Mogadishu. The road was earlier cut and
destroyed by floods.
</P>
<P>
The three agencies, the EU office in Somalia, UNICEF and CEFA
have collectively turned the responsibility of the projects to
the local authority of Jowhar town.
</P>
<P>
The governor of the Middle Shabelle region thanked them for
their unforgettable support to his people who have been suffering
poor land communication and lack of clean water.
</P>
<P>
"We used to drink straight from the river, but from now on, we
have confidence on what we're drinking," said Nur Shirbow, who
used to be a military officer.
</P>
<P>
The cost of these projects were not released publicly.
However, EU and UNICEF have entrusted the water project to a
local private agency called Farjanno for its sustainability.
</P>
<P>
Farjanno will sell the water to the public at a reasonable
price to maintain the equipments, fuel and the local staff
operating the system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
