<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Drops to All-Time Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso today
dropped to an all-time low of 30.688 pesos against the U.S. dollar
as a result of eroded investor confidence prompted actually by the
country's high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
At the Philippine Dealing System, the peso fell to 30.81 to the
U.S. dollar at one point. The central bank of the Philippines sold
dollars in a bid to stabilize the exchange rate but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said the peso was put under pressure mainly by
the high interest rates which many fear would be raised further.
</P>
<P>
Since the peso was declared floated within a wider band on July
11, the central bank has been taking a series of measures,
including a hike last week in the banks' liquidity reserve rate
from five to eight percent, to tighten the money market and defend
the peso.
</P>
<P>
However, these measures caused interest rates to rise and hurt
investor confidence at the local stock market, which fell to a
four-year low after an eight-day straight decline on Monday.
There were outflows of funds and trading at the foreign exchange
market was also affected.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said the prospects for both the peso and the
stocks are far from rosy as the currency woes sweeping the region
have not yet shown signs of termination.  
</P>
</TEXT>
