<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland to Increase Aid to Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Finland is planning to
increase its aid to developing countries next year as part of its
long-term drive to boost cooperation with these countries.
</P>
<P>
The government said in its 1998 draft budget it will provide
1.62 billion Finland marks (300 million U.S dollars), or 0.36
percent of the gross national product (GNP), to developing nations
in 1998, an 11.2 percent increase over the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget, which was submitted to Parliament today for
debate, foresees a rise in the aid to GNP ratio of 0.4 percent in
2000, and ultimately 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Finland will continue to focus its aid on African countries
south to the Sahara, including Ethiopia, Kenya, Mozambique,
Namibia, Zambia and Tanzania. It will also give aid to Palestine,
Egypt, Vietnam, Nepal and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
Finland will also allocate 226 million marks (41.5 million
dollars) to cooperation programs with middle and eastern European
countries, mainly to environmental protection programs in Russia and
Baltic countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
