<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Estonia to Cooperate in EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Estonia have
agreed to support each other for their bid to become members of
the European Union (EU), an official press release issued here
today said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached Monday during a visit to Estonia by
Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides, who started Sunday a
tour of six European nations, namely Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania,
Germany, Luxembourg and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides had a meeting with Estonian Prime Minister Mart
Siimann and held talks with his counterpart Toomas Hendrick
Ilves on the latest developments in the protracted Cyprus problem
and assured him of the Cypriot government's political will for a
solution as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Ilves briefed Kasoulides on the steps Estonia has
taken toward a free market and liberalizing its economy in view
of its preparation for EU entry.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers agreed to have regular contacts and
cooperate closely to cope with problems each country faces during
their EU accession course. Kasoulides invited his Estonian
counterpart to visit Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Estonia are the first group of countries with which
the EU has recommended to begin accession talks in the first six
months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops landed
and seized the northern third of the Mediterranean island following
a short-lived coup seeking union with Greece by some Greek
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has not been solved despite repeated
efforts by the U.N. and international community over the past 23
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
