<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania to Raise Value-added Tax, Some Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Albania will raise the
value-added tax rate from 12.5 percent to 18-22 percent from
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano, who took office a month
ago, announced the hike which was proposed by the International
Monetary Fund as a condition for providing economic aid to Albania.
</P>
<P>
In a speech last Saturday, he also announced that the ceiling
prices of petroleum products, the business tax on cigarettes and
liquor and tax on income from leasing will also be increased.
</P>
<P>
The exemption of some non-necessities from import and export
customs duties and value-added tax will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expected that this move will add billions of
Albanian lek (US$1 equals 155lek) to the financial income in the
last four months of the year, and increase the gross national
product in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In response to people's worries about price hikes, Nano pointed
out that the prices of some daily necessities will be controlled
under a level people could endure.
</P>
<P>
Albania experienced a national disturbance early this year due
to the collapse of a nationwide pyramid-scheme, which wiped out
two billion U.S. dollars worth of Albanians' money.
</P>
<P>
The current unemployment rate in Albania is 37 percent and 1.2
million of the 3.2 million population are living under the poverty
line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
