<HEADLINE> Philippine President, Cardinal to Meet on Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said
today that he and Jaime Cardinal Sin have agreed to meet again for
the third time or as often as necessary as part of the process to
foster unity among the people.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told reporters in the southern province of Sulu that he
was glad that the outspoken cardinal has agreed to meet with him
because that will help heal the wounds in the past.
</P>
<P>
Ramos was in Sulu to attend celebrations of the first
anniversary of the signing of a peace agreement between the
government and the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF).
</P>
<P>
Ramos has met twice with the cardinal in a bid to persuade him
to call off a rally against the drive to change the 1987
constitution.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos failed to persuade the influential cardinal to change
his mind and not to lead the grand rally scheduled for September
21, which former president Corazon Aquino also said she will join.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has appealed to the cardinal and other church leaders to
call off the rally, saying it will only cause disunity and open
healed wounds in the past.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' supporters have sought to change the constitution to
lift term limits of all elective government officials, including
the president.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has voiced repeatedly his determination not to seek a
second term when his single six-year term ends in June 1998. But
Ramos has also publicly supported "the people's initiative" to
change the constitution, which provides for only one single term
for the president.
</P>
<P>
Congressmen from Ramos' ruling party are now pushing hard in
the House of Representatives to pass a resolution to convene the
bicameral congress into a constituent assembly.  
</P>
