<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Criticize US Congressman For Indiscreet Remarks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- US Congressman Frank Wolf's
remarks about what he allegedly saw and heard in Tibet have
triggered an indignant response from various ethnic groups in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
People from political, legal, religious, cultural, education,
and tourism sectors gathered in Lhasa Monday to refute Wolf's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
In August, Wolf paid a five-day visit to Tibet and held a press
conference after he returned home, where he presented his "travel
notes" on Tibet. He talked about religion, culture, education,
justice, tourism, people's lives, and relations among minority
groups in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, he said that about a million people have been
killed in Tibet in the past 20 years and that Lhasa has become a
world of the Han people.
</P>
<P>
Lhada Ngawang Danzim, a renowned abbot in Tibet, said that
"Wolf's remarks are an insult to the Tibetan people. He described
Tibet as an inhuman world, something that deeply hurt the feelings
of the Tibetan people."
</P>
<P>
Cering Puncog, an official with the region's prison
administration, said that Wolf's remarks about prisons were wrong
and that the annual per capita living cost in Tibetan prisons was
2,500 yuan (about 300 US dollars), 1,540 yuan more than a Tibetan
farmer's average earnings.
</P>
<P>
He noted that prisoners enjoy free medical treatment and
receive health check-ups regularly. They are allowed to have free
time on national holidays, weekends, and traditional festivals,
and they have freedom of religion and the right to receive an
education. There are 1,170 prisoners now with education
certificates of various kinds.
</P>
