<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Criticize US Congressman for Indiscreet Remarks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that Wolf has never been to a Tibetan prison and that
what he said about them sounds like nonsense.
</P>
<P>
Wolf also said that "Tibetan culture has been destroyed." In
response, Qangngoiba, an expert on the Tibetan language, said that
before liberation, there was not a single school in the modern
sense in Tibet and the vast number of serfs did not have the right
to an education, and even in the early 1950s, over 95 percent of
the Tibetans did not know how to read and write.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 40 years, the central government spent 1.1
billion yuan on education in Tibet and Tibet now has 800 primary
schools, 100 middle schools, 16 secondary technical schools and
four universities and colleges.
</P>
<P>
Vjam Dbyangs, an expert on cultural relics conservation, said
that the central government has spent at least 100 million yuan on
the renovation of the Potala Palace and other famous temples, and
that this shows its concern for Tibetan religion.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the central government has spent 200 million
yuan repairing 1,700 monasteries and religious sites throughout
Tibet, which now has 46,000 monks and nuns.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Buddhism associations have been set up in the seven
cities and prefectures in Tibet, which also has a Tibetan Buddhism
institute.
</P>
<P>
These facts demonstrate that Wolf's remark that "Tibetans have
no right to freedom in religious belief" is but an outrageous lie.
</P>
<P>
Chen Qing, a guide from the Tibetan Regional Tourism
Administration, criticized Wolf's comments about the region having
a tight control on tourists. She said she is very busy during the
tourism season and often has to give up her weekends because of
the increasing number of foreign tourists visiting Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Wolf's remarks about what he allegedly saw and heard in Tibet
are absolutely groundless and he is just confusing black and
white, disregarding the tremendous progress that has been made in
Tibet. His anti-Chinese attempts are bound to fail.  
</P>
</TEXT>
