<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Criminals Treated Leniently </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman from Tibet's Higher
People's Court pointed out here today that the central government
requires local courts to carry out a "light punishment" policy
when sentencing Tibetan criminals.
</P>
<P>
The statement came in response to US Republican representative
Frank Wolf's claim that about one million Tibetans have been
executed or sentenced to death in China over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Wu Junqing of the Higher People's Court in Tibet Autonomous
Region called Wolf's remarks "groundless and ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Wolf made up such sensational lies just to please the
public with claptrap," said Wu. "A simple comparison of population
figures will expose the lie."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that Tibet's population stood at around one
million in the 1950s, but had shot up to more than 2.38 million by
1996, according to the results of a sample survey conducted last
year.
</P>
<P>
"How can the population double if there has been any kind of
genocide in the region?" Wu asked.
</P>
<P>
Tibet had implemented the old legal code until 1959, which was
notorious for its cruel and severe punishment of serfs. It was a
common practice then to sentence a serf to death for a minor
offense against the nobility.
</P>
<P>
"The situation was fundamentally reversed when the system of
the people's court was introduced to the region after 1959," Wu
said.
</P>
<P>
The files of the regional Higher People's Court suggested that
local courts have altogether passed sentences on some 10,000
criminals during the past 38 years. The court records from 1977 to
the end of August of 1997 show only 5,400 criminals were
convicted, many of whom were of Han and other ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
"We are very careful about meting out capital punishment," said
Wu, adding that the law on criminal procedure stipulates that
death sentences must be approved by the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, only some 1,000 criminals were
sentenced to death, death with a two-year reprieve, 20-year
imprisonment, and 10-year or above prison terms.
</P>
<P>
This does not mean crime rate in Tibet is lower than in other
parts of China, Wu pointed out. "The central government guideline
is to be lenient in meting out punishment in Tibet," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
