<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krajisnik Claims Outside Meddling Hampers Peace Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Serb member of the
Bosnian Presidency, Momcilo Krajisnik, said Monday night that
interference in the internal affairs of the Bosnian Serb republic
by certain international mediators has severely hampered the
implementation of the Dayton accords.
</P>
<P>
The Serb leader made the remarks in a meeting with Russian
Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky in Pale, the Tanjug
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik said he appreciated Moscow's stance on the political
crisis in the Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
Afanasyevsky said Russia is very concerned about the crisis and
that Serbs themselves must find a resolution at any cost, he said.
</P>
<P>
The international community should and must provide aid for the
Serb republic, but should not interfere in its internal affairs,
nor use force against it, Afanasyevsky said.
</P>
<P>
Both international mediators and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO)-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) troops in
Bosnia were supposed to help implement the Dayton accords that
ended the three-and-a-half year civil war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Tensions rose sharply last week in Bosnian Serb areas between
the 3,500-strong SFOR and local residents loyal to their wartime
leader Radovan Karadzic, as his power struggle with Western-backed
Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic was heated up.
</P>
<P>
In Brcko and Bijeljina last Thursday NATO operations
encountered resistance from local residents. Brcko people
reportedly attacked dozens of American peacekeeping soldiers,
comparing them with Nazi occupation forces during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Bijeljina spent the night on a square in front of
the police station to prevent SFOR troops from taking over the
police station and a television transmitter.
</P>
<P>
A crisis within the Bosnian Serb leadership began in early July.
</P>
<P>
Serb President Biljana Plavsic dissolved the parliament on July
3, but the decision was strongly opposed by parliament, and the
Serb government believed to be actually controlled by former
president Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court ruled last week that Plavsic's
decision was unconstitutional and invalid. Plavsic rejected the
verdict of the court.
</P>
<P>
Among the wrangling of the Serb leadership, western countries
led by the United States voiced support for Plavsic and were
trying to force Karadzic out of the political arena and bring him
to trial before the International War Crimes Tribunal in The
Hague.
</P>
<P>
On August 20, British and Czech troops of the SFOR surrounded
four police stations and one police academy in Banja Luka, a
northern Bosnian town, to help Plavsic boost her authority in the
town.
</P>
<P>
After the operation, police chiefs loyal to Karadzic were
removed from their posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
