<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for Comprehensive Peace for Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
underscored the need for comprehensive peace in the southern
Philippines to allow the government time to turn Mindanao into a
centerpiece of development.
</P>
<P>
The government and the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF)
will continue to work together to promote peace and development in
the area once torn apart by nearly a quarter-century of armed
conflict, Ramos said on the first anniversary of a peace agreement
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement is on track and we are happy to show our people
-- as well as the leaders of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) and the Organization of the Islamic Conference --
both of which supported the peace process, that the peace
agreement is working," he said in Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the government wants Mindanao to become within two
to five years an area of vigorous growth where the Filipino people
shall live in harmony in a culture of peace, unity and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He added that peace is being translated into growth as more and
more joint efforts by the government and the private sector are
attracting investments to the South.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the president said, the provinces and cities that
later comprised the Special Zone of Peace and Development in
Mindanao got only 5.4 billion pesos (207 million U.S. dollars) in
investments. The figure rose 164 percent to 14.26 billion pesos
(544 million dollars) by 1995 and would reach at least 46.32
billion pesos (1.54 billion dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
For economic development in Mindanao, the government also
carried out a series of flagship projects, investing some 16
billion pesos (570 million dollars) in the infrastructure
construction in the area.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, note that the Philippine government faces
another main block in bringing comprehensive peace to Mindanao,
where a 12,000-member rebel group called the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front still has sporadic clashes with government
troops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
