<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross: Iraq Suffering Shortage of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) has said outside help is badly needed to
improve the severe shortage of potable water in the
U.N. sanction-ridden Iraq, Iraqi newspaper "Al-Jomhouriya"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the newspaper, Post Widmer,
commissioner of the ICRC Middle East Water and Hygiene Department,
said that more than 1,000 Iraqi water-clearing stations need
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
He added that what is being done by the ICRC for repairing
these stations is inadequate because of the limited means of the
ICRC.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the ICRC working plans in Iraq are being
prepared, and that the funds needed in the water and hygiene
sector in Iraq will amount to some 5.2 million Switzerland francs
(3.54 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Most Iraqi provinces, as well as many Baghdad residential
districts, are currently suffering a shortage of potable water,
especially in the summer.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused the U.S., a member of the U.N. Sanctions
Committee, of blocking the approvement of contracts signed by Iraq
for the purchase of 285 water pumps, 13 diesel pumps, four farm
pumps and 38 water sterilizers.
</P>
<P>
The contracts are within the framework of the oil-for-food
deal, which was signed by Iraq and the U.N. in May last year and
went into effect last December.
</P>
<P>
The deal allows Iraq to sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil
every six months to buy food and medical equipment badly needed in
the country. And each contract will be approved unanimously by the
U.N. Sanctions Committee, consisting of representatives of all the
15 Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Widmer also said that the oil-for-food deal
will not cater to the essential needs of the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
