<HEADLINE> International Anti-Mine Conference Opens in Norway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Second Diplomatic
Conference on an International Total Ban on Anti-Personnel Mines,
scheduled to last three weeks, opened today in Oslo, capital of
Norway.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, about 400 participants from more than
100 countries around the world stood for one minute in silent
tribute to the memory of Princess Diana, who was scheduled to
attend the conference but was killed in a car crash in Paris
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss and try to reach an agreement on
issues concerning a total ban on producing, storing and selling
anti-personnel mines. The agreement is expected to be signed this
December in Canada and come into effect early next year.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 million landmines are now reportedly planted in
about 70 countries, killing an average 800 people a month and
injuring 1,200.
</P>
<P>
The first anti-mine conference was held in Ottawa, capital of
Canada, in October 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
