<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Foreign Debt Burden Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The foreign loan burden per
person in Bangladesh increased 19 times in the last 23 years,
according to the Bangladeshi Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita debt obligation rose from 6.59 U.S. dollars in
the 1973-74 fiscal year to 124.2 dollars in 1995-96, the ministry
said in an annual document published recently.
</P>
<P>
Since independence in 1971, foreign aid disbursement has
totaled 30.5 billion dollars, of which 48.7 percent is in grants
and 51.3 percent in loans. Of the total amount, 5.46 billion
dollars is in food aid, 9.38 billion dollars in commodity aid and
15.7 billion dollars in project aid.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the flow of food and commodity aid showed a
gradual declining trend, with food aid decreasing from 47.9
percent of total aid in 1971-72 to a mere 9.6 percent in 1995-96
while commodity aid fell from 50.8 percent to 15.9 percent during
the same period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, project aid jumped to 74.6 percent from a meager 1.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the share of bilateral aid decreased from
73.9 percent in 1971-72 to 53.5 percent in 1995-96 while
multilateral aid grew from 26.1 to 46.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the bilateral donors, Japan tops the list in terms of
cumulative disbursement, followed by the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's soft lending arm, the International
Development Association, is on the top of the list of multilateral
agencies, followed by the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's external borrowings mainly consist of medium- and
long-term debt on concessional terms with an average grace period
of 10 years and repayment period of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
They have mostly gone to the public sector, whose debt rose
from 501.4 million dollars in 1973-74 to 15.17 billion dollars in
1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The debt service payment on total public sector loans jumped
from 19 million dollars in 1973-74 to 561.4 million in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rise in debt service payment to
increasing debt, expiry of grace periods and exchange rate
fluctuations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
