<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Expects Huge Infrastructure Requirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine infrastructure
requirement is estimated to reach five billion U.S. dollars a year
in the coming years, Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista
said today.
</P>
<P>
Bautista was quoted by the Philippine News Agency as saying
that the huge infrastructure requirement is an incentive to
sustain investors' interest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said it is difficult to invite big-ticket investments
into the country, especially the provinces, if necessary
infrastructures are not there.
</P>
<P>
Considering the government's limited resources, new and
innovative schemes must be pursued to finance the country's
infrastructure requirement, he said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the use of regional cooperative initiatives and
provident funds as possible sources of financing.
</P>
<P>
At present, the government's availment of the official
development assistance (ODA) from foreign countries and some
multilateral financial bodies is limited.
</P>
<P>
To further increase investments, Bautista said, the Trade and
Industry Ministry will design an incentive package that will
encourage and enhance projects that are infrastructure-related.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
