<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Residents Enjoy Higher Living Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China's urban residents have
witnessed a sunstantial improvement of living standards over the
past five years, with the average annual per capita income
increasing to 4,839 yuan in 1996, according to a survey report
from State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The residents' annual incomes in real terms stood at 4,377 yuan
per capita in 1996, 1.8 times the 1991 figure, the SSB report
shows.
</P>
<P>
A great change took place in the income mix of Chinese urban
people during the 1991-1996 period, while the ratio of the
earnings from state and collectively-owned sectors to the total
earnings dropped to 72 percent from 74 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the proportion of earnings from other economic
sectors, including individually-owned businesses, increased
from two percent in 1991 to five percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that the income distribution mechanism was
further modified, with the income gap between higher-educated
workers and manual laborers widened considerably. The ratio
between the earnings of workers with primary school education and
those with a college degree reached 1:1.7, compared with the
1991 ratio of 1:1.2.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country is becoming a more consumption-oriented
society. In 1996, food spending decreased to 48.6 percent
of urban people's incomes, 5.2 percentage points lower than in
1991. A slight drop also was seen in the proportion of spending
on clothing, household appliances and services.
</P>
<P>
However, the proportion of spending on medicare, transport,
telecommunications, entertainment, education, culture and housing
showed an upward trend during the five years, registering increase
margins from 0.8 to 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the per capita living space reached
11.8 square meters for urban residents here, up 19.2 percent from
1991. Great improvement was also recorded since five years ago in
the housing conditions, especially the availability of a
sufficient gas supply and kitchen equipment, the SSB report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economic Condition Under Control: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today rejected calls by the business community to convene
the National Security Council to discuss the ongoing state of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said there is no need to convene the meeting as suggested
by the business community in a letter presented to him on Monday,
because the present economic condition is well under control.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen voiced their concern over the country's
economic growth, which slowed down to 5.9 percent in the first
half of the year compared with the 7.5 percent in the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Some economists earlier complained that the government
neglected economic growth by paying too much attention to amending
the country's constitution to extend the terms of elective
officials including President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos said today that he would instead meet with
government economic managers, members of the congress and business
representatives on Friday to discuss economic matters and exchange
ideas on how to sustain the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Among the topics to be discussed at Friday's meeting is the
state of the country's economic growth in relation to the current
currency problems being experienced by other Southeast Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said it is almost impossible for the government to
achieve its 7-8 percent economic growth target for the year,
taking into account the economic slowdown in the first semester
and the currency woes sweeping the whole region in the third
quarter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
