<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Graduate From IMF Supervision Soon:Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said
today that the Philippines will definitely "graduate" from the
supervision of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) before the
year is over.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told reporters in the southern province of Sulu that the
Philippines' exit from the IMF will be achieved following the
passage of the Comprehensive Tax Reform Program (CTRP) by the
Senate on final reading.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who was attending a cabinet meeting in Sulu, thanked
Senate President Ernesto Maceda for supporting the passage of the
tax measure.
</P>
<P>
The CTRP, which is expected to raise the government's revenues
considerably, is the last major component the IMF wanted the
government to adopt before the country is given a good
housekeeping report card.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the CTRP will enable the country to have a
sufficient flow of revenues support for various government
infrastructure projects and Social Reform Agenda (SRA).
</P>
<P>
The Philippines was supposed to graduate from IMF supervision
earlier had Congress passed the measure earlier this year. The
Lower House passed the measure but it hit a snag when it reached
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
But the Senate, which passed its own version of the CTRP last
week, is expected to carry the bill soon. A bicameral committee
will then discuss, finalize and ratify the CTRP before submitting
it to Ramos.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panda Gives Birth to Twins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A giant panda living in a
research center here gave birth to twins over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The panda siblings weighed 150 grams and 130 grams at birth on
August 29 at the China Giant Panda Protection and Research
Center. Mother and children are in "excellent condition,"
according to workers with the center.
</P>
<P>
Experts said giant pandas kept in a man-made environment have
difficulty getting pregrant, as the females tend to snub the
ardent males.
</P>
<P>
Less than 10 percent of the male pandas living in zoos or
breeding centers are capable of mating and the pregrancy rate
among female pandas kept in artificial environments is around 24
percent.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Chinese government and the World Wildlife
Fund, the China Giant Panda Protection and Research Center was
established in 1980 in Wolong Natural Reserve, in southwest
China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, the center has artificially inseminated 13 female
pandas. Nineteen babies were born, but only 14 have
survived. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
