<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets Trinidad and Tobago Senate President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, meeting today with Trinidad and Tobago's
Senate President Ganace Ramdial, said he hopes that Ramdial's
current China visit will help promote the friendly relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Although geographically far apart, Qian said, their cooperation
in a variety of areas has been developing well since the forging
of diplomatic ties more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government supports the exchanges
between the parliaments of the two countries, which will enhance
mutual understanding and increase friendship between the two
peoples.
</P>
<P>
China has always held that all nations, big or small, strong or
weak, rich or poor, should treat one another equally, Qian said,
noting that ties between the two countries set a fine example for
state-to-state relations.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Ramdial on China's domestic situation.
</P>
<P>
Ramdial said he hopes that his trip will help promote friendly
relations between the two countries. He expressed the conviction
that China will eventually achieve its great reunification cause.
</P>
<P>
Ramdial reiterated that the government of Trinidad and Tobago
will continue to pursue the "one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Li Zhaoxing also attended the
meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
