<HEADLINE> Banks Move Australian Share Market Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A sell-off of banking stocks
ahead of the Australian federal government's response to a report
on the country's financial system weighed on the Australian share
market today, with the bourse slipping to a three-month low.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index fell 8.9 points to 2581.9, its lowest
close since May 27 when it ended at 2578.9.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks reacted more positively after the government's
response after being marked down earlier in anticipation of that
response.
</P>
<P>
"The banks were down because of the thought of some revelations
from the Wallis report, but when it came they bounced back again
to a degree," a broker said.
</P>
<P>
Among the government's responses to the report was the ruling
out of mergers between Australia's four major banks.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 14 cents to 18.75 Australian
dollars from a low of 18.7 Australian dollars, ANZ 9 cents to 9.66
Australian dollars and Westpac Bank 16.7 cents to close at 7.727
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank dropped 15 cents to 14.7 Australian dollars,
after hitting a low of 14.46 Australian dollars at one stage.
</P>
<P>
News Corp shares jumped 13 cents to 6.3 Australian dollars and
the preferred shares rose 6.7 cents to 5.337 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index slid 13.9 points to 4160.4 while the
All Resources Index shed 5.1 points to 1350.3.
</P>
<P>
Jubilee Mining shares continued yesterday's spectacular rise,
with more than 20 million shares traded, to add another 18 cents,
or 50 percent, to 54 cents following promising drill results at
its Cosmos nickel project.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP, the country's largest company, dropped
17.6 cents to 16.86 Australian dollars and Rio Tinto 22.3 cents to
19.897 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bullion prices declined marginally from an overnight 324.75
U.S. dollars per ounce to 324.6 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 250.63 million shares traded
worth 638.77 Australian dollars (472.68 million U.S. dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises by 516 to 412.  
</P>
</TEXT>
