<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Plans Breakthrough in Economic Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China is brewing up a major
breakthrough for its economic reform, hoping to enliven the torpid
state sector after more than a decade of gradual progress.
</P>
<P>
Bold explorations are expected to be made to seek diversified
yet effective patterns of public ownership, thereby pulling
unprofitable large-and medium-sized state-owned enterprises out of
the financial mire, sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
The state plans to retain control over state ventures in basic
industries and those concerning state security and public
interests, the officials said. The rest of the more than 10,000
state-owned large- and medium-sized ventures in the nation,
especially those in competitive processing industries, will be
encouraged to switch to various forms of public ownership.
</P>
<P>
To this end, China is considering transforming some of these
enterprises into shareholding companies and companies with limited
liability, and also encouraging those with good prospects to list
on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
There are presently a total of 13,000 state-owned large- and
medium-sized ventures in China, accounting for only 3.4 percent of
the total number of the nation's industrial sector, but their tax
revenue represents 65 percent of the sector's total.
</P>
<P>
However, the financial dilemma of the state sector continues to
be the outstanding problem of the Chinese economy, in spite of the
initial success the nation has made in reforming the
macro-economic structure since 1992.
</P>
<P>
But hope returned when Chinese President Jiang Zemin called for
a powerful change in the economic reform in last May. Jiang
pointed out in a speech at the Party School of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) that public
ownership and state ownership are not the same thing, and called
for bolder exploration of new public ownership patterns that may
substantially boost the overall economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes at Two-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Rumors of an official rate
cut as early as tomorrow gripped Australia's financial markets,
causing the Australian dollar to lose half a U.S. cent in trading
and close at a two-year low.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended in Sydney at 72.65 U.S. cents, down
from 73.16 late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Market participants said they do not expect an interest rate
cut tomorrow, but sentiment for an easing has continued to weigh
on the foreign exchange market ahead of any announcement following
today's Reserve Bank of Australia board meeting.
</P>
<P>
They will be waiting tomorrow for any word from the bank.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was last at such levels in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
It finished at 88.31 Japanese yen from 88.45 and against the
Deutsche mark, it was at 1.3242 from 1.3289.  
</P>
</TEXT>
