<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Plans Breakthrough in Economic Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice-President of the Party School Wang Jiaqiu said that the
leading position of the state-owned enterprises in the national
economy is due to their control over the lifeline industries in
the national economy, rather than how many there are.
</P>
<P>
"The shareholding system has nothing to do with privatization
since the system only provides a pattern to achieve public
ownership and will bring no change to the present economic
structure where public ownership is in the leading position," Wang
explained.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed to the shareholding system as "an effective
pattern of public ownership that accords with the Chinese
characteristics and an option that may bring about a new
breakthrough in the state enterprise reform."
</P>
<P>
"Adopting the shareholding system in the state sector also
answers the need to speed up the Chinese economy which is still in
the preliminary stage of socialism," he added.
</P>
<P>
Economist Wang Jue echoed Wang Jiaqiu's view by saying that a
shareholding system could only strengthen instead of weaken the
leading position of public ownership, since it allows the state to
control a shareholding venture by taking 51 percent of its stake,
and will thereby increase the influence of the state assets to a
greater extent.
</P>
<P>
The effectiveness of the shareholding system on the state
sector has also been fully revealed in the 9,200 shareholding
ventures in the country, which have been set up on a trial basis
since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Official sources also predict that China will make new moves in
its enterprise reform, mainly in the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state is also expected to push forward reform
measures to readjust the role of the government, change the
government's mangement mode over the economy, and expedite the
transforming of financial assets into industrial capital.
</P>
<P>
The state enterprise reform, together with all other supportive
reforms, will push China a substantial step forward to reach the
goal of establishing a socialist market economy by the end of this
century, economists stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
