<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Lags Behind in High-Tech Race: IBM Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia is left behind
other nations, including Thailand and Malaysia, in high-tech
industries and Internet commerce, IBM Australia Managing Director
Robert Savage said today.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that Australians are eager to adopt new
technology and the nation possesses an advanced telecommunications
system, the Australian information technology (IT) sector is
inhibited, Savage said.
</P>
<P>
"As a percentage of the Australian stock market, high-tech
industry is barely on the radar, accounting for little more than 1
percent in 1996," Savage told a group of company directors in
Melbourne today.
</P>
<P>
Australia's share of world IT and technology exports is less
than half a percent, compared to Thailand with over 2 percent,
Malaysia and the Republic of Korea with around 6 percent, and
Singapore with nearly 8 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite our enthusiasm for technology and our highly educated
population, Australia is not in the forefront of successful,
innovative high-tech nations."
</P>
<P>
Having deeply impressed by the role the IT industry has been
playing in the U.S. economy during a U.S. visit earlier this year,
Australian Prime Minister John Howard and his cabinet have been
reviewing the country's IT industry policy in a bid to boost its
slowly growing economy.
</P>
<P>
Recent proposals on the country's IT industry policy call for
preferential policies including tax breaks for attracting overseas
investment in the industry.
</P>
<P>
But Communications Minister Richard Alston, who is in charge of
the country's IT industry, last week ruled out the possibility of
giving tax breaks to the sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
