<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Language Dominates Local Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Qamba Yang Dron was proud that
her excellent result in Tibetan language exam has helped secure
her enrolment in Beijing Tibetan Middle School this summer.
</P>
<P>
"You just cannot graduate from primary school if you fail the
language test," said the 12-year-old Tibetan girl, who could barely
speak or understand her native language years ago, living
with her parents in inland China.
</P>
<P>
However, she picked up Tibetan quickly after she attended a local
school in Lhasa, capital of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to a local educational official, Baima Tsering,
the Tibetan language is a compulsory subject throughout the
grade-school years in Tibet and other classes like mathematics,
history, music and drawing are all conducted in Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
"Students like Yang Dron will have to continue their Tibetan
language studies in Tibetan middle schools in inland China," said
Tsering. "We have kept sending good language teachers to these
schools."
</P>
<P>
He was raged against the rumor that students in Tibet are
forced to learn the Chinese language. He said the Law on
Compulsory Education stipulates that schools should ensure that
students from ethnic minority groups learn to read and write their
own languages as well as Chinese.
</P>
<P>
During their six years in primary school, students in Tibet
should spend at least 1,598 hours in learning the local
language. They begin to learn the Chinese language at Grade Three,
with 748 teaching hours altogether until graduation.
</P>
<P>
"The arrangement suggests the dominancy of Tibetan language in
local school education," said Tsering, adding that a junior high
graduate can read and write expertly in Tibetan language, a major
progress compared with old Tibet when over 90 percent of the local
people were illiterates.
</P>
<P>
"The worrying fact is that Tibetan children living outside
China find more difficulty now in using their native language,"
Tsering pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0148 </DOCNO>
