<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The inquiry into the fatal accident of Lady Diana and Dodi
Al-Fayed began on Monday. The Paris Public Prosecutor has
discovered an over high level of alcohol in the blood of their
chauffeur. The Mercedes he was driving was running at 160, if not
180, kilometers per hour. Meanwhile, the seven photographers who
pursued the car are still detained by police.
</P>
<P>
-- The Algerian press has strongly criticized authorities for
the negligence in transporting hundreds of bodies of those killed
on Friday morning by Islamic extremists to a cemetery in the
capital Algiers. The bodies, all transported on trucks and
ambulances for 25 kilometers, were lined up in the alleys of the
cemetery to let the families identify them, and the authorities
failed to provide enough plywood coffins, as a result two or
three bodies had to put into one coffin.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The press should beg pardon in the fatal incident of
Princess Diana, who would not have been killed if not harassed by
the chasers of image, who were employed by press agencies. The
media regarded Diana as their "creature" and would not stop until
they caught her. They devoured their prey, going as far as
photographing the last breaths of the adorable princess.
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with le Figaro, South African President
Nelson Mandela promised to "do his best to help his neighbors",
while in the Congo Republic, the partisans of Pascal Lissouba and
Denis Sassou Nguesso were fighting with artillery for the
presidential seat. But Mandela denied that he would monopolize the
job of mediator in African conflicts, including those of Congo
Republic and Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
