<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kiptanui Eyes at 3000m Record in Rieti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Moses Kiptanui will try to
snatch back his 3,000 meters steeplechase world record in the next
station of the athletics Grand Prix which starts on Wednesday in
Rieti of Italy.
</P>
<P>
Kiptanui is the first man to break the eight-minute mark for
the event when he set a world record of seven minutes 59.18
seconds.
</P>
<P>
But his record was surpassed by Kenyan-born Dane Wilson Boit
Kipkiter by a tenth of a second in Zurich and then Kenyan Bernard
Barmasai rewrote it in Cologne in 7:55.72.
</P>
<P>
In Cologne, Kiptanui finished second behind Barmasai in 7:56.16
-- well inside the original record. And he said afterwards he was
confident of reclaiming the world's fastest steeplechase time.
</P>
<P>
Kiptanui's compatriot Daniel Komen, the newly-crowned world
champion and world record holder over 5,000 meters, will try to
erase Noureddine Morceli's name from the record books at Rieti.
</P>
<P>
Morceli is scheduled to run in a 1,500 meters field which also
includes world champion Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco and Venuste
Niyongabo of Burundi, which means that a serious attack on
Morceli's world record of 3:28.86, also set in Rieti, is
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
On the field, Cuban triple jumpers Yoelvis Quesada and Aliecer
Urrutia, fresh from their gold and silver medal successes at the
World Student Games in Sicily, are both due to compete. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
