<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water, Sewerage Face-lift to Cost 100M Drs in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The rehabilitation of
dilapidated water and sewerage schemes in Zambia will require 100
million U.S. Dollars, Financial Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper quoted head of the water sector development
group Dennis Mwanza as saying as a result of the low expenditures
for capital investments, operations and maintenance during past
20 years, most water and sanitation schemes in Zambia are not in
good shape.
</P>
<P>
"Financial resources are inadequate to meet the costs of
extending coverage of water and sanitation to the majority of the
population, and to meet the costs of essential operation and
maintenance of facilities. Consequently in spite of very
significant capital investments, most financed by external
support agencies, the new facilities rapidly deteriorated into
disuse," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since budgetary allocations from the central government have
been low, there is need to have private investments into the
water sector, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The operation and maintenance of the water sector has also
been hampered by the non-payment of water bill by water users,
Mwanza complained.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that only 50 percent of the urban population
and 30 percent of the rural population of the country have access
to clean water. The government has set a plan to provide clean
water to all Zambians by the year 2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
