<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wanted Rasta Killed by Kenyan Police in Shoot-out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The most wanted criminal
Bernard M.T. Rasta was shot dead by Kenyan police Monday at his
home in Murang's District, the "Daily Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
During a 30-minute shoot-out, two detectives of the Flying
Squad of Kenyan police were injured and sent to a Nairobi
hospital by a police helicopter, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
A man believed to be Rasta's close associate was arrested and
a pistol and nine rounds of ammunition recovered.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Noah arap Too, Director of Criminal
Investigations, as saying that "we are sure he is the man (Rasta)
whom our officers shot dead".
</P>
<P>
Rasta, who reportedly shot dead several people, has been
wanted since 1995 with a 100,000 Kenyan Shillings (about 1,700
U.S. Dollars) reward on his head.
</P>
<P>
He first slipped through an ambush laid by more than 50
policemen from the Flying Squad at a rented house in Nairobi late
in July and survived a day-long operation to track him down.
</P>
<P>
Rasta and other two criminals were accused of masterminding
the crime wave in which several people including senior police
officers were killed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the past three weeks, Kenyan police in Nairobi have
arrested Rasta's two bodyguards and recovered two sophisticated
guns loaded with several rounds of ammunition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
