<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China's "Underground People" Disappearing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- In his novel "The Time
Machine," American science fiction writer H.G. Wells described a
futuristic society in a world where the sun and moon don't shine.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps unbeknownst to Wells, the villagers of Xi'niu, in
Pinglu country of north China's Shanxi Province, have existed in
such a place for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongqin, a farmer in the village, has been living
underground for over half a century. Gazing around her "basement
house" -- a huge pit with a square central yard and cave dwellings
on each side, adorned by several wild jujube trees and large
patches of moss in the corners -- Wang has mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
The pit covers a total area of about 0.67 hectares and is a
legacy from her ancestors.
</P>
<P>
Poverty and the rarity of stones on the Loess Plateau led to
the building of the underground houses, most of which were
constructed at least ten meters below ground level.
</P>
<P>
An earthen slope entrance led people down, and around the yard,
covering an area up to hundreds of square meters, were several
cave dwellings dug for family members.
</P>
<P>
A dry well was also needed to hold rain to prevent flooding in
the yard and to give the residents enough water to drink.
</P>
<P>
The "underground people," as they are called, go to work at
sunrise and turn in by the light of the moon, Wang says.
</P>
<P>
For many years, to live above ground was a long-cherished dream
of the poor farmers, she explains. Only the wealthiest people in
Pinglu County were able to live in traditional houses made of
stones and bricks from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
But over the past few years, more farmers in the village have
settled their families in above-ground houses paid for with
earnings from crops of fruit trees and tobacco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China's "Underground People" Disappearing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang now has to move out of her pit because of the pressure
from her daughter-in-law, who is excited about the idea of a
four-room brick house at ground level.
</P>
<P>
"I'm fed up with living in the cave dwellings that are dark all
day long and wet throughout the year," the young lady says.
</P>
<P>
"And I don't want to become humpbacked like my mother-in-law
and most of the old people here," she adds. The high humidity in
the underground house has left many of its residents with
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
Although Wang agrees that moving up has its advantages, she
still has some worries about the change. "I'm afraid that I will
not be able to get used to the weather in the upper world," she
says, explaining that this is because the underground houses are
cool in summer and warm in winter.
</P>
<P>
And like most older people there, she will grieve for the place
where most of the significant events of her life occurred.
</P>
<P>
The Pinglu government has been trying to talk all the residents
of its over 15,000 basement houses into moving above ground so
that the county can gain about 3,400 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that building brick houses on the ground
occupies less land than digging the pits and caves.
</P>
<P>
So far, only 10 percent of the county's population are still
living in the underground houses -- most of them are elderly.
</P>
<P>
"It is the trend of the times that all the 'underground people'
will say goodbye to their cave dwellings in the near future," says
the director of villagers committee of Xi'niu.
</P>
<P>
Some people have suggested that the most representative of the
underground houses should be made into tourist sites.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0160 </DOCNO>
