<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Wheat Output to Reach 16 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government's chief commodity forecaster today slightly dropped its
wheat output forecasts for the current financial year to 16
million tons.
</P>
<P>
In its latest crop report, the Australian Bureau of
Agricultural and Resource Economics (ABARE) forecast 16.208
million tons of wheat to be produced during the 1997-1998
financial year starting on July 1, 1997, marginally down from the
July forecast of 16.245 million tons.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said the seven million tons expected from the state of
Western Australia, buoyed by favorable seasonal conditions, would
help offset the overall production loss.
</P>
<P>
"Dry seasonal conditions in much of eastern Australia mean that
overall crop yields are likely to be below average in 1997,"
Stephen Beare, acting executive director of the bureau said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Wheat production for the previous financial year ending June
30, 1997, reached 23.6 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Beare said the latest meteorological data indicated below
average rainfall for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
"Based on this outlook, winter crop production in 1997/98 is
forecast to be 24.7 million tons, 28 percent below the record 34.5
million ton crop of the previous year."
</P>
<P>
Winter crops include barley, oats and sorghum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
