<HEADLINE> Sampras Knocked Out But Hingis Advances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The world number ones in
men's and women's singles had different fates in the U.S. Open
tennis tournament in New York on Monday, with American Pete
Sampras knocked out and Swiss Martina Hingis advancing.
</P>
<P>
Two-time defending champion Sampras battled three hours and 37
minutes but could not prevent himself being disposed of by Petr
Korda of the Czech Republic 6-7, 7-5, 7-6, 3-6 and 7-6.
</P>
<P>
Two light drizzles and a harder rain fall punctuated the match,
with the latter coming when Korda leading 1-0 in the fourth set.
After play resumed, Sampras took control and levelled the match by
winning the set 6-3.
</P>
<P>
But Korda came back strongly in the fifth set, breaking Sampras
in the fifth game.
</P>
<P>
Korda then exchanged powerful serves with Sampras as he
gradually gained the upperhand with his vaunted backhand drives.
</P>
<P>
Korda crushed an astounding 67 winners and drew 66 unforced
errors from Sampras.
</P>
<P>
In the quarter-finals, Korda would face Sweden's Jonas Bjorkman,
who beat Australian lefthander Scott Draper 6-3, 6-3, 1-6, 7-6 in
another fourth-round match.
</P>
<P>
Briton Greg Rusedski also entered the last eight, beating Czech
Daniel Vacek 7-6, 6-2 and 6-2, while Dutchman Richard Krajicek
beat Felix Mantilla of Spain 7-5, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
There was little surprise in the four women's matches as
Hingis, Jana Novotna of Czech Republic, American Lindsay Davenport
and Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain advanced in straight sets to
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Hingis thrashed Argentine Florencia Labat 6-0, 6-2 in 51
minutes and will next play her own doubles partner, Sanchez
Vicario.
</P>
<P>
Davenport and Novotna, also doubles partners, will meet in the
other quarterfinal match in the top half of the women's draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
