<HEADLINE> Uganda Army Rescues 32 Civilians from Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's government troops
have rescued 32 civilians from rebels of the Allied Democratic
Forces (ADF), local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rescued, including seven children below five years,
arrived yesterday at Fort Portal in Kabarole District in the west
and most of them later returned to their homes in the district,
according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The 32 civilians are part of the residents abducted by the ADF
rebels in Kihondo Trading Center in the district last Friday.
Eight of the abductees have escaped earlier.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were to send the abductees to deep mountain areas
in western Kasese District, but the Ugandan army managed to close
in on the rebels and freed the civilians before the rebels
escaped and reached their destination, Francis Kato, one of the
civilians, said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said ADF rebels abducted civilians for
military training to fill their ranks.
</P>
<P>
The ADF, with some 300 members, is a rebel group haunting in
western Kasese District. 
</P>
</TEXT>
