<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Tibetologists Refute Wolf's Remarks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of foreign experts on
Tibetan studies who are currently on an inspection tour in Tibet
have cast doubt on the validity of US Congressman Frank Wolf's
recent critical remarks about life in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Even though what I've learned is only a fraction of the entire
scope of Tibetan studies, I dare say that I know more about the
place than most westerners, like Wolf," said Prof. Colin
Mackerras, director of the Research Institute of Asian Culture at
Australia's Griface University.
</P>
<P>
Mackerras has been to Tibet three times, and to major Tibetan
communities in other provinces, including Qinghai province.
</P>
<P>
"What I saw in Tibet is entirely different from Wolf's
description," Mackerras said. "He who knows little about Tibet has
no right to discuss Tibet."
</P>
<P>
Responding to Wolf's remarks that all Tibetans support the
Dalai Lama, Mackerras replied, "I found that some do support him,
but they are in the small minority."
</P>
<P>
After six trips to leading Tibetan communities, Mackerras said
he believes that none of the Tibetan people want independence for
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Another expert, Susan Meinheit, said, "I found that Tibetan
medical skills are well developed." Meinheit visited the College
of Tibetan Medical Sciences based in Lhasa, and expressed her
satisfaction with the fact that many of the senior doctors use
traditional Tibetan healing methods.
</P>
<P>
Meinheit is fluent in the Tibetan language, which she said has
greatly enhanced her interaction with local residents.
</P>
<P>
Tibetologist Ellis Gene Smith, who works for the National
Library of Congress in the US, bought several books written in the
Tibetan language, including primers, during the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Tibetologists Refute Wolf's Remarks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Richard Strassberg, a professor of Eastern culture at
California State University in Los Angeles, noted that his
personal experiences in Tibet contradict Wolf's comment that "the
oppressed Tibetans are living under unimaginably barbarous
conditions."
</P>
<P>
"But I found many newly-built houses, which show that people
here have money to spare for the improvement of their life,"
Strassberg said.
</P>
<P>
The overseas scholars are in unanimous agreement that Tibet has
achieved progress in economic development as well as cultural
preservation. "Progress in these respects has been startling since
I last came here in 1990," recalled Graham Clarke, a British
professor at Oxford University who has visited Tibet six times.
</P>
<P>
"As many Chinese say, this has been brought on by Deng
Xiaoping's socialist policy with Chinese characteristics," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The scholars also expressed their belief that freedom of
religion is fully guaranteed in Tibet, and hoped that the
international community will understand this.
</P>
<P>
They said they have seen shrines for worshiping Buddhas set up
in almost every home, and such activities have not been blocked by
authorities.
</P>
<P>
As for the notion that religious freedom will be eradicated in
the region, Tibetan religious expert Ms. Robinson said, "That's
definitely out of the question."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the experts denied that the environment in Tibet has
been sabotaged. "It would need five days' ride away from Los
Angeles to find a place as beautiful as this," said one of the
experts. "Tibet is the least-damaged place in the world."
</P>
<P>
"I truly do not understand why Wolf made these groundless
remarks," Colin Mackerras said. "Possibly it is out of the wish of
some politicians in the United States who fear a strong
counterpart like China." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fertility Rate In Australia Reaches Its Lowest Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Many women in Australia
remained childless all of their lives, a recent data from the
Australian Bureau of Statistics showed that childlessness among
women has reached an all time high of one in four women.
</P>
<P>
A study says the fertility rate in Australia fell to its lowest
level of 1.82 children per woman in 1995 from 3.6 children per
woman in 1961 and 2.9 children in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Since 1976 it had been below replacement level of 2.1 children
per woman, that means people are not having enough children to
replace themselves, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
"Incentives need to be provided if declining fertility of
Australian women is to be addressed," Dr. Shail Jain and Professor
Peter McDonald of the Australian National University said in their
study published in latest issue of the Australian Population
Association's Journal.
</P>
<P>
Fertility rates are lower for urban women, especially for those
with low family incomes and those with high level education.
</P>
<P>
The important changes in economic and social conditions have
increased the proportion of women participating in education and
the labor force and led to changes in family demography, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
These changes include a decrease in the proportion of married
people, an increase in divorce and one parent families, and an
increased need for families to rely on two incomes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Literary Classics Presented to St. Lucia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CASTRIES, St. Lucia, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China's permanent
representative to the United Nations, Qin Huasun, today presented
a collection of Chinese literary classics to the Library of Saint
Lucia.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin told his audience at a reception here that the
collection, known as the Treasure of Chinese Classics, literally
crystallizes the cream of China's 5,000-year culture.
</P>
<P>
Consisting of 123 volumes, it is the work by more than 3,000
Chinese experts and scholars over six years, and is the largest
cultural compilation project of this century, Qin explained.
</P>
<P>
"Both China and St. Lucia have a splendid culture and fine
traditions," he noted, expressing his hope to see a starting point
for cultural exchanges between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the Treasure of Chinese Classics will help
further enhance the understanding of China by the people of
St. Lucia," the senior Chinese diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Qin and George Odlum, St. Lucia's minister
of foreign affairs and international trade, signed a joint
communique on forging diplomatic ties between China and St. Lucia.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of official relations, Qin said at the
reception, "is a great joyous event for our two countries and two
peoples, as well as an event of historical significance."
</P>
<P>
China highly appreciates the clear-cut position taken by St.
Lucia to consider the government of the People's Republic of China
as the sole legal government representing China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to some 200 quests, Qin said China views its relations
with Latin American and Caribbean nations from the global
strategic perception and the perspective of the 21st century.
</P>
