<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Investors in Kenya Rush for Treasury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Investors in Kenya have
recently be rushing to put their money into Treasury Bills (TB)
to take advantage of the high yields on government securities.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate on the 91-day bill increased by seven percentage
points from 18 percent three weeks ago to 25.263 percent at last
week's auction, according to the latest report issued by the
Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
The report said that the CBK had advertized for the sale of TB
worth 9 billion Kenyan Shillings (about 140 million U.S. Dollars)
at the auction held last week.
</P>
<P>
The bank received bids worth 11.5 billion Shillings (about 177
million Dollars) at an average interest rate of 25.831 percent,
said the report, adding that the CBK accepted bids worth 8.4
billion Shillings at an average rate of 25.263 percent.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, the Kenyan government announced that it
would allow interest rates on TB to rise in order to arrest
capital flight following the decision of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to suspend a loan package to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) was quoted as
saying that the high yields had caused a slump in activity at the
stock market as investors shift to the TB.
</P>
<P>
During the July 7 riots, the turnover at the NSE plummeted to
five million shares, the lowest traded in the history of the
market, and two weeks ago, volume of the market turnover dropped
to six million shares.
</P>
<P>
Following the rapid rise in TB interest rate, Kenya's
commercial banks are expected to start increasing their base
lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Barclays Bank in Kenya increased its base rate from
21 percent to 24 percent and the bank will also review its
savings and deposit rates, according to the bank's managing
director Peter Geer.
</P>
<P>
As a result, observers here said that the economic turmoil
caused by the IMF's loan stoppage had derailed the government's
plan of keeping inflation at single digit level.
</P>
<P>
The inflation which had earlier been estimated at 12 percent
is expected to escalate following the recent announcement of
price increases in fuel, food and other commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
