<HEADLINE> Mugabe on Forthcoming SADC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has said that regional leaders will hold consultations and
exchange views at the summit of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) which begins in Malawi on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists at Harare International Airport on
Monday, Mugabe said the SADC summit had been split into two
meetings.
</P>
<P>
One of the meetings will discuss the current status of the
SADC Organ on Peace, Defense and Security in the context of
security and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
The other will discuss issues that relate to the region, such
as trade, industrial development, food security and the looming
droughts.
</P>
<P>
He said, "there is quite a lot that we should meet and discuss
before the meeting in Malawi."
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, President Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique and his
Botswana counterpart Ketumile Masire arrived in Harare to consult
with Mugabe on the SADC summit.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the three presidents will also discuss the
situation in the Great Lakes region, particularly the sanctions
imposed on the military junta in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow, Mugabe flies to Tanzania where he has been invited
in his capacity as chairman of the Organization for African Unity
(OAU) to attend a meeting of leaders from the countries of the
Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are meeting to discuss lifting of sanctions
against Burundi where a military government led by Pierre Buyoya
seized power in July 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
