<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean President Opposes Pardoning Ex-Presidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam today opposed pardoning two jailed former presidents by
the Mid-Autumn Festival holidays beginning September 15.
</P>
<P>
"I will consider the pardon sometime during my presidential
term. But now is not the time," Kim, whose term expires February,
said about the ex-presidents, Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo.
</P>
<P>
By making his decision public, Kim is expected to turn down his
ruling New Korea Party (NKP) Chairman Lee Hoi-chang's proposal of
a pardon of the ex-presidents when they meet on August 28.
</P>
<P>
"Pardon for Chun and Roh is a grave issue which should not be
resolved by political considerations that ignore historical and
judiciary meaning," Kim was quoted as saying by aide Moon Jong-soo.
</P>
<P>
Debate flared last weekend when both ruling and opposition
leaders called for releasing the former presidents, now serving
jail sentences on mutiny charges, by the Mid-Autumn Festival.
</P>
<P>
The move is interpreted as a wooing gesture to Kyongsang
Provinces' voters, the hometowns of Chun and Roh, in view of the
coming presidential election in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
While talking to the press today, Moon Jong-soo ruled out the
possibility of suspending prison sentences for the two former
presidents instead of a pardon before the traditional holidays.
</P>
<P>
"If the time is ripe for a pardon, the president will make a
decision under full legal procedure," Moon said, "this does not
mean Chun and Roh have to live out their full jail sentence."
</P>
<P>
"As the issue of pardon has come out in public, although we
cannot specify when, it will be reviewed continuously and carried
out at a point when public consensus is reached," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
