<HEADLINE> UNIP Says Government Should Pay Kaunda More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The opposition UNIP party led
by former President Kenneth Kaunda said the 238 million Kwacha
(about 183,000 U.S. Dollars) the government has paid Kaunda since
he stepped down in 1991 is far below his entitlement.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Kaunda's press aide Muhabi Lungu
as saying here Monday that the government disclosure of the money
was meant to create the impression that it is not ill-treating
the former president, who had ruled Zambia for 27 years until
1991, when he was defeated in the elections.
</P>
<P>
"Why are they disclosing this information now? it is true this
money has been paid but Dr Kaunda is also entitled to a house,
office accommodation, four vehicles and a lot more," Lungu said.
</P>
<P>
He said Kaunda is by law supposed to have a house built or
bought in a place of his choice but the government has denied him
all those privileges.
</P>
<P>
The government Sunday denied claims that Kaunda has been
neglected.
</P>
<P>
chief government spokesman David Mpamba said Kaunda has
received a total of 238.5 million Kwacha in retirement benefits
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
"Zambians must know that the government is not as heartless as
the impression being created by Dr Kaunda. There is no way that
this government has wished or will ever wish Dr Kaunda dead,"
Mpamba said.
</P>
<P>
This referred to a light wound on the head of Dr Kaunda when
he was fired at by a policeman at a rally in the central town of
Kabwe last week. After that, people from the opposition United
National Independence Party (UNIP) considered the government as
heartless in treating the former president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
