<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Syria are planning to introduce a system
whereby each side will gradually exempt the other from customs
duty on exchanged goods in implementation of a 1975 trade
agreement, semi-official Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Damascus and Amman are taking a preliminary step by preparing a
short list of goods exchanged by the two countries to exempt them
from customs duty, the paper quoted Jordanian Minister of Trade,
Industry and Supply Hani Moulki as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the two sides are expected to reach a
final agreement on exemptions during a meeting he will hold with
Syria's Minister of Economy and Trade Mohammad al-Imadi in Cairo
this month.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's gasoline prices have gone up by 1.2
percent, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The price of 96 octane gasoline rose by 1.2 percent to 3.37
shekel (about 0.96 U.S. dollar) a liter and the price of 95
octane (unleaded) gasoline also rose by 1.2 percent to 3.37
shekel a liter.
</P>
<P>
However, diesel fuel for commercial vehicles went down in
price by 1.5 percent and heating fuel's cost also dropped.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Israeli Infrastructure Ministry said that the
price changes were caused by the rising cost of oil products in
the Mediterranean area.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Member states of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) need to invest more than 10 billion U.S. dollars in
industrial projects over the next two years to diversify their
income resources, according to a bank report.
</P>
<P>
GCC officials have begun discussions on projects worth some 18
billion dollars, but the 10 billion figure is more realistic,
said the report by Bahrain's Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The report did not specify the projects, but it said the
investment is a move by GCC states to diversify their income
resources, which are heavily reliant on oil exporting.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Bahrain, the United Arab
Emirates, Kuwait and Oman. The six countries control nearly 45
percent of the world's proven oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's foreign currency reserves reached a
record high of 18.25 billion U.S. dollars, following a 258
million dollars increase in August.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Israel figures available today indicate that the
reserves increased in January-August by about 6.78 billion
dollars, a rise of 58.5 percent since last December.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the August increase in reserves to
government transfers and changes in the banks' deposits with the
Bank of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Israel has not intervened in trading and has not
had to purchase foreign currency from the private sector since
June 20, due to the introduction of foreign currency
liberalization measures taken by the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
But from the beginning of the year to mid-June, the Bank
of Israel was allowed to purchase a total of up to 7
billion dollars in foreign currency from the private sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
