<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Satellite Starts Operation in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The commercial operation of the
Philippines' first satellite, Agila II, is targeted to start in
October, Mabuhay Philippines Satellite Corporation President and
Chief Executive Officer Cesar Reyes was quoted as saying today by
the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Agila II was launched on August 20 at Xichang, China, and
settled successfully into its 144 degrees east longitude orbital
slot. The satellite, worth 243 million U.S. dollars, remains in
perfect condition in that slot, the agency quoted Reyes as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said Agila II deployed its solar panels 190 minutes after
take-off and has since gone on to deploy its telecommunications
and broadcast transponders, antennae and other devices and to
employ its earth sensors and earth coverage horns.
</P>
<P>
After two maneuvers, Agila II is already in its station-keeping
box, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said full control of the satellite will pass on to the
Mabuhay Satellite Space Center at the Subic Bay Freeport Zone.
</P>
<P>
Payload in-orbit testing will then be immediately performed by
the center's Filipino satellite engineers, with technical support
from Canada, Reyes said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
