<HEADLINE> China Revamps Old Cartoon Hero for Modern Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese artists have
revamped the image of an old cartoon star in an effort to compete
with the influx of hip cartoon characters from overseas.
</P>
<P>
"Sanmao," or "Three Hairs," is perhaps the country's most
famous cartoon character, created by Zhang Leping in the
1930s. The story of the street waif reflects the life of
old China.
</P>
<P>
Artists in the 1990s have decided to equip Sanmao, whose image
is protected by the Chinese patent law, with computers, cars and
fashionable clothes, to make him more attractive to young
fans.
</P>
<P>
So far it has worked. The new and improved Sanmao appeared at the
ongoing Eighth National Book Fair in Changchun, capital city of
northeast China's Jilin Province. Some 3,000 Sanmao cartoon books
have been ordered, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Li Mingci, the publisher from the Children's Publishing House,
said that even some Hong Kong publishing houses are interested in
buying the Sanmao copyright.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, official media have repeatedly
called for more Chinese-made cartoon stars in response to the
invasion of foreign heroes who they said "in some ways are not
suitable for children." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
