<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Peace panels of the Philippine
government and rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) met in
the southern city of Cotabato today for the seventh time to
discuss an agreement for a general ceasefire in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators, working under the committees on the cessation
of hostilities, are also to discuss moves on how to convince
thousands of war evacuees in the southern provinces of Cotabato
and Maguindanao to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports cited that the evacuees refuse to go back to
their domain due to fear that military-MILF skirmishes might again
occur after their fierce encounters last June and July.
</P>
<P>
The peace panels from both parties are due to sign today an
interim agreement on this matter.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice-chairman for political affairs,
stressed that both panels are now ready to present their
respective recommendations for the groundwork of the ceasefire
accord.
</P>
