<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SW China Panzhihau to Become Top Rare Metals Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Panzhihua Iron and Steel Co.,
set up in the mid-1960s in southwest China's Sichuan Province,
plans to become a major world producer of vanadium and titanium,
China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country's top producer of vanadium and titanium, the
company plans to continue expanding its vanadium and titanium
processing capacity in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
The annual production capacity of vanadium pentoxide will reach
9,000 tons in 10 years, said the company's president Hong Jipi.
</P>
<P>
Panzhihua has 20 percent of China's iron reserves, 64 percent
of vanadium reserves, and 93 percent of titanium reserves.
Vanadium and titanium are rare minerals widely used in iron, coal,
military and aerospace industries.
</P>
<P>
China had to import vanadium products, as it could not process
vanadium-bearing ores. But things began to change in 1971 when the
company made a breakthrough in processing such ores.
</P>
<P>
China is now the world's fourth largest vanadium producer and
its vanadium products are exported to Japan, Europe and North
America, Hong said.
</P>
<P>
To improve the quality of its vanadium products, the company is
upgrading the current production facilities and will import a new
vanadium production line from Germany.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company, which incorporates 72 member units,
will push forward the shareholding system, the president said.
</P>
<P>
One of its member companies issued A shares last year on the
Shenzhen stock market, and raised 84.7 million yuan (10.2 million
US dollars). And another one is getting ready to issue H shares in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Panzhihua produced 3.27 million tons of iron and
2.82 million tons of steel. And its output of vanadium and
titanium products both exceeded 100,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Able to Protect Plants in Three Gorges, Experts Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese botanists say that the
plants in the Three Gorges in the middle section of the Yangtze
River will not face extinction as a result of the construction of
a reservoir there.
</P>
<P>
"We have built more than ten reserve areas and forest parks to
evacuate the valuable plants," said Xu Tianquan, a botanist from
the Chinese Academy of Sciences who is attending an international
botany meeting here.
</P>
<P>
"We have adopted various biological methods, including
establishing a gene warehouse, to ensure that we can have all the
DNA samples of the plants in the Three Gorges," said Huang
Hongsheng, another botanist.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of rare plants, some of them belonging to families
dating back 400 million years, have been found in the Three Gorges
area, which covers 62,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the Three Gorges Dam early next century, the
world's biggest hydro-electric project, will cause the rise of the
Yangtze River, which might change the environment and climate,
scientists said.
</P>
<P>
Some people have expressed their concern that the diversity of
plants will be affected.
</P>
<P>
Xu revealed that the establishment of the Three Gorges
Botanical Garden in Yichang in Hubei province has been approved by
the State. Some species that cannot survive in the Three Gorges
will be protected in the garden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-cancer Medicines, Research Progressing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese pharmaceutical
manufacturers will put more time, talent and money into
researching world-level, anti-cancer traditional Chinese
medicines, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine
(SATCM) is scheduled to develop several such medicines before the
turn of the century -- used to help alleviate cancer victims' pain
around the world, said Yu Shenglong, SATCM deputy director.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) statistics indicate more
than six million people died from various forms of cancer in the
world last year.
</P>
<P>
In China, 1.6 million cancer cases are reported
annually. Cancer is the second leading cause of death in the
country, behind heart and brain vascular diseases.
</P>
<P>
More than two million patients currently suffer from malignant
tumors. One in 200 Chinese families is affected.
</P>
<P>
However, only 20 percent receive surgery, due to various
reasons, including financial and physical situations.
</P>
<P>
Between 10 and 15 percent are suitable for chemical and
radiation therapies, known to cause side effects, said Hong Jing,
SATCM official in charge of scientific research.
</P>
<P>
China began researching anti-cancer medicines from Chinese
herbs in the 1950s, Hong said.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 herb varieties were tested. Of those, 200 were
deemed effective in improving patients' physical conditions.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 of the drugs have been approved and are being used
clinically.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have so far developed 20 preparations out of Chinese
herbs. Five have been recognized as new traditional Chinese
medicines by the State.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
