<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Increase Primary School Enrollment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is targeting
to raise the rate of enrollment of primary school pupils to 85
percent by the year 2000, according to local press today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local press on Monday, Deputy
Minister of Education and Culture Bujiku Sakila said that the
recently published basic master plan for education in Tanzania
will enable his ministry to improve the quality and quantity of
primary level education in several aspects.
</P>
<P>
Sakila said that his ministry plans to improve the quality of
the teaching staff by introducing teachers' centers all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect aimed to raise the standard of education
focuses on the special project to improve teaching of the three
basic subjects -- mathematics, English and science.
</P>
<P>
The present rate of primary school enrollment in Tanzania
stands at 77 percent. It reached 98 percent in 1981 but
drastically dropped to 65 percent later due to several factors
including the general fall in the standard of education,
according to Sakila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
