<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Raises Prices of Petroleum Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- After months of waiting, the
Indian government has finally taken a decision on a hike in prices
of petroleum products with effect from midnight Monday, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision, reached after an hour-and-a-half-long cabinet
meeting late Monday night, took into account the objection of the
left parties and ensured that the price increase is relatively
moderate.
</P>
<P>
The left parties, which are the major constituents of the
ruling United Front, have been opposed to the price rise, which
they say would impose an additional burden on the poor.
</P>
<P>
According to the cabinet package, prices (excluding taxes) of
gas is up by 1 rupee (about 2.86 U.S. cents) per liter, diesel by
1.8 rupees (about 5.14 cents) per liter and cooking gas by 15
rupees (about 42.86 cents) per cylinder.
</P>
<P>
However, kerosene, "the fuel of the poor," has been spared.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also approved proposals for phased dismantling of
price and marketing controls over petroleum products and for
lowering excise and customs duties, details of which will be
announced within six weeks.
</P>
<P>
The price hike had become inevitable because of burgeoning
deficit resulting from huge government subsidies to the prices of
petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The accumulated deficit, which stood at 155 billion rupees
(about 4.43 billion dollars) at the beginning of this financial
year (from April 1997 to March 1998), had reached 182 billion
rupees (about 5.2 billion dollars) by June 30, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
