<HEADLINE> Obuchi to Be New Japanese Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Keizo Obuchi will be Japan's new
foreign minister and Hiroshi Mitsuzuka may be reappointed as the
finance minister in Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's new
cabinet, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kanezo Muraoka, who now serves as the chairman of the Liberal
Democratic Party's (LDP) Diet (parliament) Affairs Committee, will
likely become the chief cabinet secretary, Kyodo news service
quoted the party sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and LDP leaders have been negotiating the makeup of
the cabinet, which is to be reshuffled after Hashimoto's
September 11 re-election as the party president.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, former LDP vice president and former chief cabinet
secretary, would replace Yukihiko Ikeda, while Muraoka will
succeed Seiroku Kajiyama, who has said that he would resign from
his post upon a cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Within the LDP, Hashimoto plans to have Koichi Kato retain his
post as secretary-general, the No. 2 post within the ruling party,
while Taku Yamasaki will maintain his post as chairman of the
Policy Affairs Research Council, the sources was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is assured of a second two-year term as LDP president
as no rival candidates are expected to challenge him when the
registration for candidacy in the party presidential race ends on
September 8. A cabinet shake-up is expected after the LDP Diet
members vote on the party presidency in a meeting scheduled for
September 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
