<HEADLINE> Foreign Tourist Spending in Indonesia Up 6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreign tourist spending in
Indonesia increased 6 percent to 2.64 billion U.S. dollars in the
first half of this year over a year earlier, a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals in the country in the January-June period
totaled 2,019,334, up 1.6 percent from the first half of last
year, Minister for Tourism, Post and Telecommunications Joop Ave
told the parliament in a hearing Monday, official sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
"We expected to see between 5.3 million and 5.5 million
international visitors this year, up by between 5.2 percent and 9
percent from the total number in 1996," the minister was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is optimistic about achieving the
projection as the number of foreign tourist arrivals is usually
higher in the second half.
</P>
<P>
The government originally targeted receiving between 7.2
billion and 7.8 billion dollars from between 5.3 million and 5.7
million overseas visitors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country received 5.13 billion dollars in foreign
exchange spending from 5 million tourists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
