<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to See Lower Tapioca Output Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Tapioca production
is predicted to be at 15.2 million tons next year, down about 14
percent from this year.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was made by the Thai Commerce Ministry after it
conducted a survey on major tapioca growing regions nationwide
last week together with leading tapioca traders and producers
associations in the country.
</P>
<P>
Planters are tending to cultivate other cereals that yield
higher returns such as sugar cane to survive the country's
economic crisis because they lack confidence in export prices of
tapioca, said Pracha Charutrakulchai, director general of the
Foreign Trade Department under the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Pracha said that the total cassava growing area in the country
will drop to 5.85 million rai (0.94 million hectares) next year
from the current 6.6 million rai (1.05 million hectares).
</P>
<P>
The yield per rai (0.16 hectare) will also fall to 2.26 tons
next year due to drought in some areas, Pracha said.
</P>
<P>
In northeastern Thailand, drought is expected to destroy 30 to
50 percent of tapioca crop next year, he added.
</P>
<P>
The department is also concerned that 1.5 million tons of
tapioca pellets exporters have in stock will face export problems
next year, Pracha said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there are some 150,000 tons of tapioca flour
remaining in warehouses in Thailand, waiting for export by the end
of this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government and exporters are joining forces to accelerate
exports to reduce current stocks by the end of the year, he added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
