<HEADLINE> Suspended Thai Finance Firms to Lay Off Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- As many as two-thirds or about
12,000 employees in the finance sector of Thailand are expected to
lose their jobs in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
The 58 finance firms, whose operations have been suspended by
order of the government because of their deep indebtedness and
mismanagement, currently employ about 18,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
Once the firms have completed their merger and acquisition
plans in the next few months, 12,000 employees would be laid off
immediately, according to Labor and Social Welfare Ministry
officials.
</P>
<P>
The high rate of job loss has caused concern to the ministry
because the laid-off employees will still have financial
commitments to meet, such as paying housing or car installments,
and the day-to-day needs of feeding their families.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will accelerate job expansion in the urban and
rural areas in preparation for the jobless, officials at the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Economic slowdown has forced many companies and factories in
the country to reduce the size of their staffs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
