<HEADLINE> Libyan Suspect Agrees to Extradition to Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A Libyan man arrested in Rome has
agreed to accept extradition to Germany to stand trial on charges
he helped blow up a West Berlin nightclub in 1986 that killed two
U.S. soldiers and a Turkish woman, judicial sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Mousbah Eter Abulgassem, 40, could be sent to Germany
within the next 20 days, although extradition from Italy normally
require 40 days, Italian judicial authorities added.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 people were also injured in the nightclub
frequented by U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Following the blast, then U.S. President Ronald Reagan ordered
reprisal bombing raids on the Libyan cities of Tripoli and
Benghazi.
</P>
<P>
Abulgassem agreed to be extradited during questioning by a
court of appeals judge at Regina Coeli prison, where he has been
held since police arrested him here last Tuesday on an
international warrant issued by Germany.
</P>
<P>
Abulgassem fled Germany in late July following his release from
custody, while awaiting trial on charges of involvement in the
La Belle nightclub blast.
</P>
<P>
Italian anti-terrorist police questioned Abulgassem last week
after a raid on a Rome apartment. The raid also resulted in the
detention of three other suspects, Libyans Hanna Ben Amer and
Khaled Ettir and Italian Nerina Bernabei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
