<HEADLINE> Russia Welcomes Asian Banks' Investment: PM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin made this appeal
today at the opening ceremony of the 14th Conference of
Representatives of the Asian Bankers Association (ABS).
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said that Russia's investment environment has been
considerably improved.
</P>
<P>
This year is a turning point to the country's economic
development with slumps in the gross domestic product (GDP) curbed
and people's income grown moderately. Russia has also seen a
stable financial situation, in which inflation has dropped
remarkably, bank loans increased and interests rate lowered.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said that Russia is to make more efforts to
further improve investment climate in 1998. Measures to be taken
include cutting the financial deficit, lowering national debt
rates, carrying out taxation reforms and protecting investors.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the government and the Central Bank should
help create favorable conditions for investments to go into
high-tech and strong and promising enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin sent a letter of
congratulations to the conference on the same day. He expressed
the hope to further enhance the cooperation between Russian and
foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Bankers Association consists of more than 200 banks
in the Asian-Pacific region. This is the first time that the
association held its conference in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
