<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Generation of CPC Leaders, China's Reunification (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the 1990s, especially after the 14th CPC National Congress
in 1992, the third generation of CPC leaders, during the
complicated transitional period, applied the "one country, two
systems" principle to a range of issues related to the return of
Hong Kong, making Deng's principle a reality.
</P>
<P>
In consideration of the unco-operative and negative actions
from the British side, the CPC Central Committee developed a
policy of "taking ourselves as the mainstay" and dealt reasonably
with the British in accordance with National People's Congress
(NPC) and NPC Standing Committee decisions.
</P>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee then took a series of measures, such
as the establishment of the Preliminary Working Committee for the
Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) and the Provisional Legislative Council, to clear
away any obstables that might hinder a smooth transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
In the process of recovering Hong Kong, the CPC Central
Committee had insisted on a policy of "catering to the Hong Kong
people and relying on them". This policy has been conducive in
drafting the Basic Law, inviting advisors on Hong Kong affairs,
establishing the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR and the
Selection Committee for the HKSAR's first government. It has also
been helpful in implementing a series of Hong Kong policies like
the principle of "one country, two systems", "the Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong", "a high-degree autonomy in Hong Kong",
and "maintaining stability and prosperity in Hong Kong." As a reult,
Hong Kong has eventually returned smoothly to China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin said that China's resumption of sovereignty over
Hong Kong is the first stop in the great cause of reunifying the
motherland, which is followed by the issues of Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Generation of CPC Leaders, China's Reunification (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee has also placed great importance on a
smooth transition of Macao and on developing relations with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and Portugese governments signed a joint
declaration on Macao in April, 1987. The Chinese government
declared that China would resume sovereignty over Macao on
December 20, 1999 and would use the "one country, two systems"
principle.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of Macao, which embodies this principle, was
officially published in March, 1993, after more than four years of
work. Negotiations have been held on three major
issues: the localization of public servants and laws and the
official status of the Chinese language. The Macao issue is
expected to be solved properly.
</P>
<P>
Since January, 1979, when the NPC Standing Committee issued the
"Letter to Taiwan Compatriots", the CPC has formulated a range of
policies toward Taiwan so as to develop relations across the
Taiwan Straits, promote economic cooperation and trade, and
increase visits and trust between the two sides under the basic
principle of "peaceful reunification, one country, two
systems".
</P>
<P>
On January 30, 1995, Jiang Zemin delivered a speech,
"Continuing the Struggle for a Fulfilment of the Great Cause of
Reunification of the Motherland", in which the principle of
"peaceful reunification, one country, two systems" was explained
and eight views and proposals on developing relations across the
straits were put forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Generation of CPC Leaders, China's Reunification (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang Zemin proposed that the two sides, as a first step, hold
talks "under the principle of one China, formally putting an end
to hostilities across the Taiwan Straits".
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the two sides then do their duties in
safeguarding China's sovereignty and territorial integrity and
make plans for the further development of relations across the
straits.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "political differences should not influence
or interfere in economic cooperation across the straits" and that
"steps should be taken for the realization of direct mail,
shipping and air links" between the two sides. Jiang's speech was
widely praised and well received by the people inside and outside
China.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the NPC Standing Committee and State
Council departments have issued major provisions and regulations
on Taiwan. And visitors have been increasing in number. In 1996
alone, 1.72 million Taiwan residents visited the interior areas of
China.
</P>
<P>
The development of relations across the straits and a peaceful
reunification of the motherland have become a historical trend.
</P>
<P>
It is reasonable to think that the CPC, which has successfully
resumed the excercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong, will be able
to lead the Chinese nation to another victory in the coming
century. China's success in solving the Hong Kong issue by using the
principle of "one country, two systems" will certainly have a
profound impact on the return of Macao to the motherland and the
sovling of the Taiwan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
