<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos Becomes AIPO's Seventh Member </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Laotian Parliament was
accepted Monday as the seventh member of the ASEAN
Inter-Parliamentary Organization (AIPO) at the organization's 18th
General Assembly held in Bali, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Laos now joins Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam as AIPO members, reports reaching here today
from Bali said.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar just joined ASEAN in July this year.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) now groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also adopted a resolution that admits another new
ASEAN member, Myanmar, as an AIPO special observer. Myanmar, like
Brunei, has not received full membership to AIPO because it does
not have a legislative body yet.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the Indonesian House of Representatives Wahono said
that AIPO's decision to admit Laos was additional proof of ASEAN's
consistent policy in building the Southeast Asian region into a
solid group.
</P>
<P>
He said AIPO was looking forward to seeing a settlement to the
internal conflict in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The six-day annual forum, which started Monday, will discuss
economic, social and organizational matters.
</P>
<P>
Beside the member countries, observer delegations from
Cambodia, Australia, China, the European Parliament, South Korea,
New Zealand, Papua New Guinea and Russia also attended the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
A member of the assembly's Steering Committee Taheri Noor said
the meeting was expected to draw up a resolution to help ASEAN
governments cope with the monetary turmoil in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said AIPO was likely to suggest that ASEAN governments make
use of a joint monetary institution already approved last month to
help countries which suffer from the overpriced U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Currencies in Southeast Asian countries have come under fierce
speculative attacks following de facto devaluation of the Thai
baht and the Philippine peso in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
