<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Generation of CPC Leaders, China's Reunification (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The reunification of China has
been the historical mission of Chinese leaders in the past, but it
is the present generation of Communist Party of China (CPC) leaders,
with General Secretary Jiang Zemin as the core, that has made the
idea of "one country, two systems" a reality.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan have been an inseparable part of
the Chinese territory since ancient times, but Hong Kong was
occupied by the British for more than 156 years, Macao has been
occupied by the Portugese, and Taiwan has been under the rule of
the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong and Macao and the solving of the Taiwan issue for the great
cause of the reunification of the motherland is the wish of all ethnic
groups, including the people of Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
China made a big step in this direction on July 1 this year,
when the return of Hong Kong became a historical feat of the
third generation of the CPC leaders.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s and 1960s, the first generation of the CPC
leaders, headed by Mao Zedong, while insisting on China's
sovereignty over Hong Kong, worked out a plan in line with actual
conditions to develop closer ties with Hong Kong and support the
economic development of the region, thus laying a solid foundation
for solving the Hong Kong issue in the future.
</P>
<P>
The second generation of the CPC leaders, headed by Deng
Xiaoping, with strategic insight, wisdom and bravery, put forward
the creative principle of "one country, two systems" and applied
it to the solving of the Hong Kong issue in the 1970s and
1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Thailand to Fall Short of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The regionwide economic
slowdown would reduce international tourist traffic and foreign
tourist arrivals in Thailand in the next two years may not attain
the target, the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) conceded.
</P>
<P>
TAT Governor Seree Wangpaichitr said Monday that it would be
unlikely for TAT to reach the target of attracting 17 million
foreign tourists in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
He said TAT would strongly promote tourism in the provinces as
part of the strategy to extend the stay of tourists.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will officially launch an "amazing Thailand"
promotional campaign in January for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the last few years, foreign tourist arrivals in Thailand are
between 6 and 7 million.
</P>
<P>
Although the depreciation of the Thai baht could make Thailand
a cheaper tourist destination, several other currencies in the
region have also depreciated, reducing Thailand's competitive
edge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
