<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Tobacco Money's Influence on Lawmakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Legislators who received
contributions from tobacco companies were three times more likely
to have voted to block spending to help states fight cigarette
sales to minors, according to an anti-smoking group's analysis.
</P>
<P>
The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) requested that 34
million dollars be distributed to states to enforce new federal
rules designed to prevent tobacco sales to teens.
</P>
<P>
An attempt to provide the full amount was blocked in July. A
Senate committee voted to provide just 4.9 million dollars, and
the full Senate voted 52-48 to turn back an amendment by Senator
Tom Harkin, a Democrat from Iowa, that would have added the
remaining funds.
</P>
<P>
An analysis of campaign contributions from tobacco companies
shows that senators who opposed Harkin's amendment had received 15
times more tobacco money during the last election year than did
supporters of the FDA funding.
</P>
<P>
The Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids said that of the 47 senators
who had received money from the tobacco industry, 83 percent voted
to table Harkin's amendment. Of the 53 senators who took no
tobacco money, 25 percent voted to table the amendment.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, in the House of Representatives, a committee that
voted to give the FDA 24 million dollars to fight teen smoking,
and an amendment for the full 34 million dollars was
defeated. Lawmakers who voted against the money took, on average,
five times as much money from the tobacco industry as their
colleagues, the financial analysis found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
