<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Develops Livestock Breeding, Fishery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is making efforts to
develop livestock breeding and fishery, encouraging local private
and foreign investments in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the country's livestock and
fishery production registered a growth of 9.7 percent in the
1996-97 fiscal year ending March over the previous fiscal year due
mainly to increase in both meat and fish production.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the livestock breeding and fishery sector
 reached 269.54 million U.S. dollars in 17 permitted projects at
the end of July this year, according to the latest official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in the sector reportedly came from
Thailand, China, Japan, Bangladesh and Singapore. Companies from
these countries have been forming joint ventures with Myanmar's
state enterprises to engage in the production and export marketing
of fish, prawn and marine products in the country's coastal areas
including those in Tanintharyi division and Rakhine state.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar began granting fishing rights and initiated joint
fishery development programs and formation of joint venture
enterprises with both foreign and local companies in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Besides permitting foreign investors to undertake related
livestock and fishery industry such as cattle breeding, pig and
poultry farming, construction of ice, canning and fish meal
plants, and cold storage, Myanmar also allows local private
entrepreneurs to operate leasable fisheries and grants cultivable
waste and fallow land for them to undertake livestock breeding and
fishery on commercial basis as well as to import offshore fishing
vessels.
</P>
<P>
To promote private sector's activities in the industry, the
Myanmar government established in February 1996 the Livestock
Breeding and Fisheries Development Bank, partly capitalized with
private shares, extending financial assistance to the
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has a long coastal line of 2,832 kilometers and the
total area of swamps along the coast is about 500,000 hectares
providing a good basis for the development of shrimp and prawn
culture.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar exploited about 590,000 tons of marine products
annually in the past few years out of the maximum sustainable
yield estimated at about 1.05 million tons per year.
</P>
<P>
The freshwater fish and marine fish production of the country
registered an annual growth of 8.9 and 39.5 percent respectively
in the 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Total exports of the livestock and fishery sector in the same
period reached 121 million U.S. dollars with fish and prawn as
the major export items.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen here said that the livestock breeding and fishery,
one of Myanmar's productive sectors, showed vast potentials for
further expansion by effectively utilizing and sharing the rich
resources and attracting more foreign and local investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Approves 4 Billion Dollar Loans to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of
Japan has signed an agreement with the Bank of Thailand to offer 4
billion U.S. dollars in loans to Thailand to help it prop up its
foreign reserves, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The loan signed Monday is the largest provided by an individual
country to Thailand in the rescue package led by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
It is also the largest financing offer parallel with the IMF
made by the Japanese bank, which extended 1 billion dollars in
loans to Mexico in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand Governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi said that the
funds from Japan will be used as standby credits to shore up
Thailand's official foreign reserves, which has dropped to 27.9
billion dollars as of August 14.
</P>
<P>
The funds match those extended by the IMF, with disbursement
conditional on Thailand's meeting IMF-set economic targets,
including keeping foreign exchange reserves at 23 billion dollars
for this year.
</P>
<P>
Funds from the Japanese loans are to arrive in Thailand by
September 10 and annual interest on the yen loans is 2.75 percent
with repayment terms set for five to seven years, Chaiyawat said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the World Bank Monday announced it
would lend 25 million dollars to Thailand for studying ways to
restructure the finance sector, including how to protect public
deposits.
</P>
<P>
The bank is expected to approve the funding on September 11,
Thai government spokesman Vorathep Rattanakorn said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
