MEXICO CITY, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
economic news briefs from the Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- South Korea's Samsung Electronics will increase
investments in Mexico, as it expects to open a commercial office
here and establish an industrial complex in the northern city of
Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
The company has committed to offer the best services and to
launch into the Mexican market products of the highest quality and
competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- cargo ship traffic through the Panama Canal in
the first seven months was 4 percent down from to the same period
of 1996, Canal Administrator Alberto Aleman Zubieta said.
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- In Colombia, the most widely affected by
the climatic phenomenon "El Nino" is coffee, which could
lose at least one million bags, experts said.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Import dues in Uruguayan seaports dropped from
160 U.S. dollars a ton to 140 dollars, the second low since the
National Seaports Administration (NSA) was established in 1995.
</P>
<P>
NSA president said he intended to continue to lower dues to 30
dollars a ton in a bid to achieve a higher competitiveness in the
region.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- General Motors, the U.S. auto maker, decided to
invest between 300 to 350 million dollars in a Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) country.
</P>
