<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science and Technology Contributing More to China's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The acreage for grain
production in China has been dropping for the past five years, but
output hit a record of 490 billion kg last year, and science and
technology had a role in this.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology contributed nearly 40 percent to China's
agricultural development, helping increase per-ha grain output by
some 500 kg in the past five years, according to a recent State
Statistical Bureau report.
</P>
<P>
The central government had many key projects to promote
agriculture through science and technology during the period, and
more than 300 new varieties of crops have been developed,
increasing rice output by 10-15 percent and soybean output almost
100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The amount of chemical fertilizers grew 37 percent, and China's
per-unit output of rice, wheat, and corn is from 26 to 50 percent
more than the world average.
</P>
<P>
The influence of science and technology can also be felt in
other areas. In the past five years, the country has had an annual
average increase of 20 percent in science and technology spending,
amounting to 91.4 billion yuan last year. It now has more than 2.7
million people working in the field, 130 percent more than for
1991.
</P>
<P>
The strategic role of science research in economic growth
became more defined during the period. Three billion yuan was
spent on state natural science fund projects, key lab programs,
and key research.
</P>
<P>
The number of advanced state labs grew from 74 in 1991 to 153
by the end of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
