<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korda Downs Sampras in U.S. Open Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Petr Korda of the Czech
Republic upset world number one Pete Sampras in five thrilling
sets in the fourth round of the U.S. Open tennis tournament here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Korda battled three hours and 37 minutes before dumping the
American star and two-time defending champion 6-7, 7-5, 7-6, 3-6
and 7-6.
</P>
<P>
Two light drizzles and a harder rain fall punctuated the match,
with the latter coming when Korda leading 1-0 in the fourth set.
After play resumed, Sampras took control and levelled the match by
winning the set 6-3.
</P>
<P>
But Korda came back strongly in the fifth set, breaking Sampras
in the fifth game.
</P>
<P>
Korda then exchanged powerful serves with Sampras as he
gradually gained the upperhand with his vaunted backhand drives.
</P>
<P>
Korda crushed an astounding 67 winners and drew 66 unforced
errors from Sampras.
</P>
<P>
In the quarter-final, he would face Sweden's Jonas Bjorkman,
who beat Australian lefthander Scott Draper 6-3, 6-3, 1-6, 7-6 in
another fourth-round match.
</P>
<P>
Briton Greg Rusedski also entered the last eight, beating
Daniel Vacek 7-6, 6-2 and 6-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
