<HEADLINE> Thailand Lifts Ban on Islamic Dress in Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Education Ministry
has lifted the ban on Islamic religious dress in state-run
schools, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The change was announced by Deputy Education Minister Areepen
Uttarasin Monday, the Bangkok Post said.
</P>
<P>
School authorities in the Muslim-dominated provinces of Satun,
Yala, Pattani and Narathiwat have been informed of the lifting of
the ban, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The move was made to end long-standing conflicts with Muslim
parents in the four southernmost provinces, where Muslim parents
usually sent their children to private or Muslim schools instead
of state-run schools due to the ban, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry will advise Muslim students to dress in
white and blue, the common school uniform color.  
</P>
</TEXT>
