<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Chicken Exports Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports of frozen
and processed chicken rose 10 percent in terms of both value and
volume during the first half of this year compared with the same
1996 period.
</P>
<P>
A total of 87,200 tons of the products, worth 6.3 billion baht
(247 million U.S. dollars), were shipped during the said period,
according to Foreign Trade Department figures available today.
</P>
<P>
The main market was Japan, which consumed as much as 65 percent
of Thailand's frozen chicken exports and 81 percent of its
processed chicken.
</P>
<P>
However, growth of frozen chicken exports to Japan dropped
slightly this year, as prices of the Thai products were higher
than those from China, Brazil and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Europe, the second largest export market for Thai frozen
chicken, showed promising increase in consumption, as two
diseases currently affecting the European Union's livestock
industry -- madcow disease and classical swine fever -- led to a
fall in beef and pork consumption in some European countries.
</P>
<P>
The increase was also attributed to the fact that 21 Thai
poultry producers had received EU quality standard certification
for imports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
