<HEADLINE> Maradona Tells of Pain of Addiction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, September 1 (Xinhua) - Argentine soccer star
Diego Maradona said in an emotional phone call to local television
that a suspension would strip too much joy from him.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell all those who are already giving me up for dead
that I'm already carrying too heavy a cross with this addiction
for them to come along. They want me off the soccer pitch, which
is where I feel happy," Maradona said in the phone call.
</P>
<P>
He did not deny that he had taken prohibited substances before
failing a dope test last week.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "I don't know what the second test result is going
to be," he said. "And if it's negative, what happens? I've got to
play on Wednesday."
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old Boca Juniors star tested positive in the first
doping test after a league match last week.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the explanation by his agent Guillermo Coppola that
he had been framed, Maradona said, "I don't want the people to
say 'They planted this on Maradona, they planted that on
Maradona.'" 
</P>
</TEXT>
