<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Dry Spell Threatens China's Autumn Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The worst drought in two
decades is threatening China's autumn harvest, and efforts must be
made to prepare for an extremely long period of difficulties
caused by the drought, the State Drought-relief Headquarters and
the Ministry of Water Resources warned.
</P>
<P>
This summer, large areas of north of the Yangtze River have
been hit by the worst drought since 1970s, affecting 23 provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities, covering over two-thirds of
the country in the past two months, with the dry spell lasting
more than 100 days in some places, today's China Daily quoted
sources at the headquarters and the ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
In late June and early July, a record 20 million ha of crops
were affected, the largest drought-stricken areas in the past two
decades, experts said.
</P>
<P>
"Although heavy rains brought by Typhoon Winnie between August
18-22 have eased the heat wave in Shandong and Anhui provinces in
east China, and in Heilongjiang, Liaoning and Jilin provinces in
northeast China, some six million ha of crops are still suffering
from the drought," said one expert.
</P>
<P>
Over the last few weeks, water shortage has jeopardized a large
number of rice fields along the upper and middle areas of the
Yangtze River. Henan, Hebei, Shanxi and Hubei were the worst-hit
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Efforts taken so far have not only ensured the normal
irrigation of crops and farmland in the large-scale irrigation
areas but also met the irrigation needs of 33 million ha of
autumn crops.
</P>
<P>
An estimated six billion kg of crops and 360,000 tons of fruits
have been saved thanks to the widespread use of a
drought-resistant chemical preparation nicknamed "dragon of arid
areas", which can preserve soil and crop moisture under scorching
sunshine, said officials with the headquarters.
</P>
<P>
All government departments of water resources, agriculture,
finance, power, and weather forecasting should co-ordinate
drought-relief efforts, and extensive water conservation projects
should be built, the headquarters and the ministry demanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interbank Rate Soars in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The interbank overnight rate
rose to a historical high of 40 percent Monday in the Philippines
as banks sought limited funds in the market to cover the higher
liquidity reserves required by the Philippine Central Bank,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a purely market-driven rate. The central bank's
borrowing rate is still at 12 percent," a trader at a medium-sized
bank was quoted by local newspaper Manila Bulletin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Liquidity is tight as banks tried to cover the higher liquidity
reserve requirement of the central bank, which has continued to
refuse lending overnight money, the trader said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the central bank raised liquidity reserves or the
amount of funds banks are required to park in government
securities to eight percent of deposits from five percent after
the peso-dollar rate hit a low of 30.45 pesos to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso was trading at an average of 30.267 pesos to a dollar
Monday, up 0.08 centavos from last Friday's average close of
30.352 pesos, after opening at 30.08 pesos to the greenback.
</P>
<P>
Treasury bill rates also soared to five-year highs Monday amid
central bank efforts to rein in liquidity that could be used for
speculation on the peso.
</P>
<P>
The average rate for the bellwether 91-day Treasury bills
surged to 19.326 percent Monday from 14.188 percent last week,
while the rate for the 182-day bill rose sharply to 20.083 percent
from 15.817 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, battered by prospects of higher interest rates
caused by the government's tightening of money in circulation to
support the peso, local stocks fell to another record low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
