<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Manufacture Cars in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Daewoo will be able
to manufacture cars in Ukraine as it is expected to sign an
agreement on September 3 to establish a joint venture with the
Ukrainian automaker AvtoZaz.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo plans to invest 150 million U.S. dollars to modernize
AvtoZaz and install a new assembly line. Under the terms of the
draft agreement, the South Korean company has to reinvest its
profits in the joint venture in a period of ten years.
</P>
<P>
Annual production is expected to reach 150,000 cars in four
years, including 80,000 modernized versions of AvtoZaz's Tavria
cars, 25,000 Opel cars and 45,000 Daewoo sedans. The capacity will
finally climb to 250,000 automobiles per year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the joint venture will put out 300,000 car
engines, one third of which will be exported to European
countries, one third to CIS countries and the rest to be sold in
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting between Ukrainian Prime Minister Valeriy
Pustovoitenko and Daewoo's Chairman Kim Woo Jung on August 29, Kim
set a precondition for the establishment of the joint venture --
to write off AvtoZaz's debts and exempt the plant from all taxes
for ten years.
</P>
<P>
Kim also urged the Ukrainian government to impose a 20 percent
import duty and a 10 percent excise duty on vehicles produced by
other foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian parliament then adopted a law writing off
AvtoZaz's debts but declined to raise import and excise
duties. The parliament also refused to exempt the joint venture
from taxes.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko viewed the parliamentary rejection not as a
tragedy. He said the Ukrainian government is interested in foreign
investment in AvtoZaz as well as the presence of Daewoo in the
Ukrainian market.
</P>
<P>
After pledging assistance to the joint venture, the Ukrainian
prime minister asked Daewoo to invest in other sectors of the
Ukrainian economy such as the shipbuilding industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970902.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Leads Team Qualifying of World Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Svetlana Khorkina lead
Russian team to scored 153.301 points to stage ahead in the
women's team qualifying round at the world gymnastic championships
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Khorhina, winner of the uneven bars at last year's
championships, collected top marks in the vault, beam and uneven
bars and also tops the all-round qualifying with a score of
38.824, a full half point in front of China's Kui Yuanyuan.
</P>
<P>
China, a disappointing fourth at last year's Olympics, came in
second with 152.045, followed by defending world champions Romania
in third on 151.469.
</P>
<P>
The top positions were not expected to change on Tuesday when
the event is completed, with the few remaining teams, led by South
Korea and Uzbekistan, posing little threat of an upset.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine finished fourth wothout their injuried top gymnasts,
world and Olympic all-round champion Lilia Podkopayeva and
promising newcomer Viktoria Karpenko.
</P>
<P>
France confirmed their status as one of the sport's developing
powers after moving into fifth ahead of struggling Atlanta Olympic
Champion the United States, who finished the day clinging to the
sixth and final qualifying position, narrowly ahead of Belarus.
</P>
</TEXT>
